Cuban authorities detained 30 dissidents to stop them from organizing a demonstration.

Clashes broke out after a county sheriff and his deputies attempted to evict peasants occupying disputed land; the two deputies and one peasant were killed in an initial confrontation and 12 people were killed total.
Rumors of a plot to free the jailed leader of a Jan. 6 coup attempt provoked street protests; rioters burned a police-fire station; at least 13 protesters killed by soldiers.

target1: Reputed member of the outlawed Tonton Macoute militia

More than 1,000 protesters called for the ouster of foreign minister Marie-Denise Jean-Louis because they felt she had not done enough to protect Haitians working in the Dominican Republic.

A pro-Aristide demonstration was broken up by police wielding nightsticks.
A Haitian photographer documenting how gas stations are favoring soldiers was detained and beaten up and his camera was also stolen.
Aristide supporters demonstrated at the site of a 1988 massacre; police beat and arrested some of the demonstrators.

Several hundred young Aristide supporters demonstrated; police tried to break up the protests but the demonstrators kept moving to different locations around Gonaives; a man accused of being a police informer was beaten by protesters.
Unknown assailants in a passing car shot and injured Senator Thomas Eddy Dupiton along with 2 other people.
One photograph-carrying Aristide supporter was killed and ten others were wounded.
notes: Coded as an  etype 2 because demonstration seemed to have been happening when soldiers killed someone; however, it does not say explicitly that there was a demonstration going on

issuenote: Pro-Aristide businessman Antoine Izmery helped organize a protest to mark the one-year anniversary of the arrests of three pro-Aristide demonstrators; leaflets were distributed of Aristide; five demonstrators arrested.
notes: Coded as an etype 1 because it states that Antoine Izmery helped organize the protest

elocal: Cap-Haitien; Estere; Gonaives and Saint Marc
issuenote: Several people were indiscriminately hit with batons, resulting in two people injured, one of them a nine-year old child; similar acts of repression in Estere, Gonaives and Saint Marc, where soldiers shot and wounded a person.
notes: Not specified if citizens were pro-Aristide or the reason for the repression

elocal: Cap-Haitien; Estere; Gonaives and Saint Marc
issuenote: Several people were indiscriminately hit with batons, resulting in two people injured, one of them a nine-year old child; similar acts of repression in Estere, Gonaives and Saint Marc, where soldiers shot and wounded a person.
notes: Not specified if citizens were pro-Aristide or the reason for the repression

elocal: Cap-Haitien; Estere; Gonaives and Saint Marc
issuenote: Several people were indiscriminately hit with batons, resulting in two people injured, one of them a nine-year old child; similar acts of repression in Estere, Gonaives and Saint Marc, where soldiers shot and wounded a person.
notes: Not specified if citizens were pro-Aristide or the reason for the repression

elocal: Cap-Haitien; Estere; Gonaives and Saint Marc
issuenote: Several people were indiscriminately hit with batons, resulting in two people injured, one of them a nine-year old child; similar acts of repression in Estere, Gonaives and Saint Marc, where soldiers shot and wounded a person.
notes: Not specified if citizens were pro-Aristide or the reason for the repression

issuenote: A group of Pro-Aristide demonstrators outside the National Palace were chased by armed civilians.
notes: Coded as escalation to an etype 4 because demonstrators were chased by armed civilians

target2: National Front for Change and Democracy
issuenote: Evans Picot, of the pro-Aristide National Front for Change and Democracy, was shot and wounded in the arm by unknown assailants.
City workers and some police occupied city hall before police cleared the building on September 8.
An Aristide supporter put up photographs of Aristide and was arrested and severly beaten.
notes: Start and end date coded as date event was reported by human rights monitors in Haiti

issuenote: A vehicle the U.N.-O.A.S. was traveling in was surrounded by government forces and hit with rifles and batons.
notes: Coded as an etype 3 because soldiers and police worked together with the goal of causing damage to the vehicle; event date not specified so date of article coded as start and end date

issuenote: Violence broke out after Mayor Evans Paul was being reinstated as Mayor of Haiti; at least 5 people were killed and 31 were wounded; Aristide supporters were shot, beaten, and stabbed and a gunman fired at Paul's vehicle as he left.
notes: Police also seem to be complicit in attacks; one mayoral aid was turned over to citizens by police and beaten and no arrests were made

issuenote: An Aristide supporter was dragged out of a church service by armed guards and shot dead; two other people were also killed in the violence; armed thugs also beat Aristide sympathizers outside of the church.
A former Army officer was shot dead at a gas station; not clear if this event was linked to the killing of the Aristide supporter at church.
Armed civilians took over the state TV station.
Aristide opponents rioted against the U.N. and some pounded on a car carrying foreign journalists.
notes: Some of the protesters were armed and because they pounded on a car, coded as an etype 4

issuenote: Small groups of Aristide opponents protested foreign intervention.
notes: No details given about location of protest; vague

issuenote: A demonstration against Aristide was held.
About 50 people, including members of the paramilitary group Macoutes, took part in an exhibition in support of former dictator Duvalier.
notes: Coded as an etype 1 because Macoutes played an important role in organizing exhibition

issuenote: 300 protesters demonstrated near the National Palace against Aristide's expected return under a U.N. plan to restore democracy to the country.
Armed men blocked eight members of the State Audit bureau from their office.
notes: Coded as an etype 3 because armed men worked together to block state audit bureau workers

issuenote: Armed civilians pulled up outside the hillside Hotel Christopher as the capital's mayor, Evans Paul, was meeting with a group of teachers; he managed to escape without being hurt but after he left the armed men began beating Paul supporters.
notes: Coded as an escalation to an etype 10 because police joined in the fighting against a mayor's supporters

issuenote: Premier Robert Malval installed new directors of state radio and TV; about 20 men, some armed, occupied the lobby, saying they would not honor the new appointments.
notes: Coded as an etype 10 because Premier decision was challenged with arms and policeman let event occur

actor1: Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti
issuenote: Pro-military activists shut down most of the capital by calling a general strike to demand that U.N. envoy Dante Caputo be expelled from Haiti and Duvalierists included in the Aristide-backed transition.
Police and military attaches fired in the air; attaches beat street merchants, forced them to flee, and shot at dogs in the street.

actor1: Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti
issuenote: A demonstration against the U.N. envoy and Aristide was held by the Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti.
Rioting occurred against U.S. and Canadian troops and children were kicked off the bus on their way to school by armed men.
notes: All actions in this event coded as same event because the issue is the same and there is a short time interval

issuenote: About 200 Haitians, protected by police, maintained a peaceful anti-U.N. vigil.
notes: Coded as separate event because non-violent vigel held overnight and this is different from violent riots

issuenote: Three members of a Miami-based television crew were arrested at gunpoint and taken to a military barracks and threatened with death because they were accused of being United Nations military operatives.
Justice Minister Guy Malary was assassinated by gunmen believed to be army-backed; two of his bodyguards and his driver were also killed.
notes: Coded as an etype 10 because government official targeted and actors are strongly suspected of being supported by the army

issuenote: A government hostage was taken by armed civilians and police never intervened.
notes: Coded as an escalation to an etype 10 because police failed to intervene in the hostage situation and this strongly implies police support for violence against government

issuenote: Sergeant Fleurand Dieuseul was killed Thursday by gunmen.
notes: Coded as an etype 8 because Sergeant was target of violence

issuenote: A protest was held against Aristide and the United Nations.

actor1: Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti militants
issuenote: Soldiers showed up to the Belance house and took Alerte; the soldiers attacked her with a machete and hacked her arm off and sliced up her tongue, face and ear.
Haitian paramilitary soldiers hacked and beat citizen Alerte Belance with machetes, then left her for dead; she survived.

Two gunmen, accused of being members of army-backed gangs, dragged Haitian citizen Orilia Joseph out of her home, beating her as they tugged her down the crowded street; part of her remains are found the next day.

actor1: Supporters of Lt. Gen. Raoul Cedras
issuenote: A general strike was called by supporters of army commander Lt. Gen. Raoul Cedras.
notes: Not specified how many people participated in general strike; article only states that a general strike was called

issuenote: Deputy Samuel Milord of the pro-Aristide National Front for Change and Democracy was abducted by armed men.
Houses of two relatives of Deputy Milord were attacked by army-backed gangs.
notes: Date of event not specified so date of deputy's abduction coded as start and end date

actor1: Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti
issuenote: Protesters demanded the resignations of Aristide and Malval if the U.N. plan is not implemented by Oct. 30.
Seven civilian army auxiliaries beat up, robbed and then dragged a street vendor into her home and raped her.
notes: Cautiously coded as an etype 7, but could be a criminal act and not repression

issuenote: Two radio stations were closed down for playing a Pro-Aristide message and a radio journalist and two technicians were arrested.

Pro-Duvalier political parties called a general strike to protest Aristide's return and demanding the resignation of Prime Minister Malval and to press the government to seize foreign-owned gas depots.
notes: Coded as an escalation to an etype 9 because gunmen forced bus drivers to discharge passengers

issuenote: About 200 rightists marched to demand the replacement of Aristide.

actor1: Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti
issuenote: A coalition of 20 small right-wing political movements demanded the resignation of Aristide, army commander Lt. Gen. Raoul Cedras and U.N. envoy Dante Caputo.

actor1: Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti
issuenote: A general strike called by the Front for the Advancement and  Progress of Haiti to protest a U.N.-imposed international embargo against the country and to press its demands to have the presidency declared vacant and a new head of state chosen.
notes: Initially called as a two-day strike but second day called off

target1: Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti
issuenote: A mob of people hacked off the arms of Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti member Paul Issa and set him afire, and stoned one of the front's leaders to death, Emmanuel Constant.

actor1: Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti
issuenote: About 200 dwellings were destroyed in a fire believed to have been started by the Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti; witnesses claim that armed men doused the shacks with gasoline and lit them.
notes: Disparity in number of deaths, probably less than 10; coded as issue1 13 because attack was likely retribution for killing of Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti members in slum on the same day

issuenote: About 30 protesters opposed to Aristide demonstrated to demand suspension of the constitution and dissolution of Parliament and Aristide's presidency.

Pro-Aristide Assembly President Firmin Jean-Louis was punched in the face by a member of parliament when he attempted to close the session for lack of a quorum; the fighting revolved around the legitimacy of 13 legislators elected January 1993.
Thousands of right-wing protesters demanded the dissolution of the parliament and the appointment of a civilian committee to end the political crisis.
notes: Coded as an etype 1 because protesters were brought in trucks to protest and this strongly implies organization

issuenote: About 1,000 members of the Congress of National Salvation demonstrated against the United Nations embargo in front of army headquarters.
notes: Event date not specified in article, so an educated guess was made

issuenote: At least 15 business associations forced their businesses to close to protest the fuel embargo that crippled Haiti's economy; only hospitals and clinics remained open.
notes: Coded as an etype 1 because business organizations forced businesses to close in protest; therefore, this is coded as a demonstration and not a worker's strike

issuenote: Attackers fired bullets and tear gas at the house holding pro-democracy group members; armed soldiers are reported to have joined in on the raid.
notes: Exact number of deaths unknown but higher than 10

issuenote: Nine soldiers climbed a steep area to investigate young men hiding out after peasants reported seeing them bathing in a river and bamboo sleeping mats drying outside a cave; the rebels started firing at the soldiers and the soldiers retreated.

actor1: Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti
issuenote: About 2,000 Haitians protested the UN-imposed embargo and for a replacement for exiled President Jean-Bertrand Aristide; the protest was called by several anti-Aristide groups.
Two days after the incident with rebels on February 3, soldiers arrested a dozen known Aristide sympathizers and torched eight peasants' homes.
notes: Coded as a separate event from February 3 rebel attack because rebel supporters and not the rebels themselves were the targets of violence

issuenote: Armed civilians abducted deputy government prosecutor Laraque Exentus and his brother from their home.
30 people were killed in a military sweep.
notes: Exact event date not given; a start and end date were approximated

issuenote: Armed civilians abducted Sylvain Morrisseau, coordinator of the Front of Reorganized Associations.
notes: Coded as an etype 7 because activist group leader was abducted

issuenote: An army officer was killed by unknown assailants.
notes: Coded as an etype 8 because army officer was killed but reason for murder was not specified

actor2: Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti militants
issuenote: Armed civilians and FRAPH militants raided a pro-Aristide neighborhood, shooting into the air and beating people; some residents were arrested and jailed at the local army outpost, and a judge and his assistants were roughed up.
The 26-year-old leader of a pro-democracy group was arrested and mistreated.

actor3: Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti
issuenote: An Aristide partisan was beaten and hacked to death by 10 men, including a soldier, two special police agents, and two members of the far-right paramilitary group the Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti.
Pro-army militants ran five U.N. observers, who were checking reports of human rights abuses, out of Hinche while army soldiers stood by.
notes: Event may have happened on either 3/23 or 3/24, so 3/23 coded as start date and 3/24 coded as end date

issuenote: About 500 demonstrators blocked the arrival of a French ship carrying humanitarian aid because France was one of the primary supporters of the worldwide oil embargo on Haiti.
Armed civilians opened fire at soldiers stationed at a military outpost; the soldiers fired back and the attackers fled; no injuries reported.

Soldiers went into Bassin Caiman, an Aristide stronghold; they fired weapons, broke down doors, stole livestock, torched fields, and burned down 100 houses and hacked a young man to death; it is unknown if others were injured or killed.
More than 40 people were killed in a military sweep.
notes: Exact event date not given; a start and end date were approximated

issuenote: In a search for an Aristide supporter, armed civilians struck and fatally injured two children.
notes: Event date not specified in article, so middle of the month was coded as start and end date

target1: Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti militant
issuenote: A Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti militant, Pierre Paul Camille, was the victim of assault and battery, presumably by Aristide partisans.
Soldiers looking for armed Aristide partisans shot into the air, rousted people from their beds and beat them up; the soldiers returned hours later, and fired at embarking fishermen, with 28 killed.
notes: Some disparity on total number killed by soldiers; most recent death count coded

issuenote: Army-backed gunmen broke down doors, shot two Aristide supporters inside their shacks and dragged the two others outside to kill them.

Shouting epithets against international observers, 20 armed Haitians, some of them police, stopped 2 U.N. vehicles carrying security officers; the armed men searched the vehicles, seizing one weapon and three portable walkie-talkies.
A Canadian journalist was detained for 48 hours and beaten.
Marie Auxiliaries Decossa, an activist with a small business association, was killed by a group of five armed men, two of them in army uniforms.

Armed civilians beat a visiting Haitian-American after seizing him on a street with four other people  and he was beaten with a stick and slapped on his ears with open palms; all five were released the next day
20 rebels fired on a military outpost and were chased by military reinforcements; two rebels and a bystander were killed.
Police-linked gunmen shot at Bien-Aime, an Aristide activist.
A boat with 400 Haitian refugees had warning shots fired at it by four policemen, setting off a panic in which 200 were thrown overboard and 30-40 people drowned.
notes: Coded as an etype 7 because police were trying to prevent refugees from leaving; coded as Nan L'etat because event happened 300 yards off the coast

issuenote: Soldiers stopped 15 people trying to get on a boat and beat them and took their money.
12 young Haitians were allegedly gunned down trying to free the country.
notes: Cautiously coded as an etype 7, but may not have been government forces who killed the 12 men

issuenote: About 200 Haitians protested against the United Nations embargo and United States intervention and in support of the military.
notes: Coded as an etype 1 because rally was advertised on the radio

actor1: Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti
issuenote: A demonstration was held against Aristide.
notes: Coded as a separate event from July 14 demonstration because the actors seem to have been different

issuenote: Cpl. Mandelus Norelus detained a man accused of stealing fruit, cut off part of his ear, made him eat it and then carved the initials S.H. - for Saddam Hussein - into the man's buttocks and beat him.
notes: Event date not specified; middle of month coded as start and end date

issuenote: Cpl. Norelus arrested and beat a Catholic priest.
notes: Event date not specified; middle of month coded as start and end date

issuenote: A near riot occurred at a food distribution center, with police lashing people with belts and switches as they struggled to get into the building for a handout.
A protest was held against the U.S. and U.N.
notes: Coded as an etype 1 because leaflets were handed out to get people to participate in the demonstration and this strongly implies organization

issuenote: Armed men showed up at the house of Bien-Aime, an Aristide activist, and pushed his wife around and tore her blouse.
notes: Coded as last day of July because exact event date not specified

issuenote: Soldiers and armed civilians attacked Senator Georges, shooting him in the back and in the arm.
Militias roughed up Haitians at a refugee processing center.
Soldiers arrested, beat and detained citizens on the streets after dark.
The bodies of two men, both shot and with straps cinched around their necks, were dumped in the middle of a busy street.
notes: Cautiously coded as an etype 7, but responsibility for deaths unknown

issuenote: A pro-military demonstration was held outside the United States embassy.
notes: Event date not specified; date of first mention coded as start and end date

issuenote: Petionville Mayor Lydie Parent and her brother Senator Clark Parent were victims of a shooting and teargas attack at their home; a relative in the house was injured.
notes: Coded as an etype 8 because Mayor and Senator were targets

issuenote: A Libete weekly newspaper street seller was threatened at gunpoint and another was thrown into the truck of a car and driven away.
notes: Coded as middle of month because exact event date not specified

issuenote: Father Jean-Marie Vincent, a close adviser of Aristide, was gunned down by armed men outside the Congregation of Montfortain Fathers headquarters.

actor1: Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti
issuenote: 2,000 to 3,000 pro-military demonstrators rallied against  a U.S. invasion, the international trade embargo, and also Aristide.
As United States warships appeared off the coast of Haiti, armed civilians shot into the air and broke up a church service.
notes: Coded as an 8 for issue1 because U.S. warships off the coast, but not certain this is the reason for the shotting at the church

issuenote: Pro-army militants beat up people as they tried to pick up leaflets dropped from American planes.
A pro-military government protest was held against Aristide and the U.S.

Outside army headquarters, hundreds of people, some wearing T-shirts declaring ''No To Intervention,'' urged army chief Lt. Gen. Raoul Cedras to hold firm and pleaded with the United States to avoid a military invasion.
notes: Difficult to determine if this protest was the same as one from previous day, so cautiously coded as separate event

issuenote: A pro-Aristide demonstration was held.
notes: Very little information given in article was event

issuenote: A pro-Aristide demonstration occurred.
notes: Very little information given in article was event; coded as a separate event from other September 19 demonstration because article says events were separate

issuenote: Several thousand people demonstrated to show Aristide, urged that military coup leader Lt. Gen. Raoul Cedras be imprisoned and hailed Americans; police moved in clubbing several demonstrators with sticks and the gun butts.
notes: Very difficult to determine which events from September 19-20 are separate events

issuenote: A demonstration of thousands of Aristide supporters was broken up by police; one man was beaten to death by police; after this man was killed, demonstrators began throwing rocks and pieces of concrete at police, and one policemen was injured.
notes: Very difficult to determine which events from September 19-20 are separate events

issuenote: A demonstration supporting Aristide was held.
notes: Very difficult to determine which events from September 19-20 are separate events

issuenote: A small protest after U.S. troops landed was broken up.
notes: Target coded as U.S. because protest occurred while troops landed; coded as issue1 8 because protest seems to have been about U.S. intervention, but the article does not say explicitly what the protest was about

issuenote: Haitians mobbed another Haitian, beating, choking and grabbing him; the reason for the attack is unknown.
notes: Not clear if victim was killed

issuenote: Pro-Aristide demonstrators protested against Cedras.
A pro-Aristide demonstration was held in Cap Haitien.
notes: Very little information provided about event

issuenote: A pro-Aristide demonstration was held.
notes: Coded as single event because it is not specified how many spontaneous demonstrations occurred

issuenote: About 1,000 Aristide supporters broke into the headquarters of the Patriotic Action Committee, injuring four people and sacking the building.
Anti-Aristide legislator Pierre Francois Vital was chased by a crowd into a police station.
About 100 demonstrators threw rocks at police headquarters, a former torture site.
Demonsrators protesting against Cedras were tear-gassed by police and the police then dragged at least two demonstrators inside a building.
A pregnant woman was pushed in the back by one policeman, then kicked in the stomach by another and fell on the sidewalk.
Pro-Aristide demonstrators held a protest.
Hundreds of Haitians looted recently abandoned police and military barracks.
Hundreds of pro-U.S. demonstrators surrounded the police precinct headquarters.
Hundreds of pro-U.S. demonstrators thronged outside Haitian army headquarters where military leader Lt. Gen. Cedras met for two hours with U.S. Ambassador William Swing and Lt. Gen. Hugh Shelton.
45 people, including two Haitian soldiers, looted a food depot and were arrested.
Several military regime supporters were killed in retaliation for an earlier crackdown on pro-Aristide demonstrators.
About 2,000 people rioted at a relief feeding center, fleeing when American military police drove up, then resumed the looting once the military left.
A U.N. Development Program warehouse was ransacked and 11 tons of food taken.
notes: Difficult to determine if this event is separate from riot at relief feeding center on same day

issuenote: Abandoned military and police outposts were ransacked, a rural sheriff was detained by civilians who also turned guns over to U.S. forces.
A pro-Aristide demonstration of about 200 people turned violent when members of the Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti threw rocks at demonstrators and hit some with batons.

A grenade attack on Aristide and Mayor Evans Paul supporters killed between 4 and 9 people and wounded at least 62 people; demonstrators surrounded the house where the grenades were suspected of coming from and hurled bricks at the building.
notes: There are disparities in the number of people injured and killed in the attack so the most recent numbers were used

issuenote: Several hundred people pillaged a grocery store.
Three or four army auxiliaries were killed in a clash with a mob of people in front of the Holiday Inn.
notes: Difficult to determine if this is a separate event or part of an escalation from another event

issuenote: An Aristide supporter was killed with a bullet to the head.
notes: Coded as an etype 4 because actor not specified; also, difficult to determine if event was separate event  or part of another

issuenote: A march of 5,000 pro-democracy demonstrators was broken up by pro-Army militiamen, who tore apart a loudspeaker truck at the front of the pro-Aristide march, shooting out its tires and pouring gasoline around it.
notes: Difficult to determine from article if people were actually killed during this event so coded a 0 for deaths

issuenote: A pro-democracy demonstration with thousands of people was held.
notes: Very little information given about event

issuenote: A pro-democracy demonstration was held.
notes: Very little information given in article about event

issuenote: About 2,000 people looted a warehouse of sugar, rice and condensed milk.
About 2,000 people mobbed a warehouse where U.S. troops were handing out sugar and other dry goods; one soldier fired a warning shot in the air while others tried to force people to form lines.
Churchgoers held a protest against the government.
notes: Many  of the participants in this event went on to participate in another pro-Aristide demonstration later in the day; this event coded as a separate event

issuenote: Hundreds of people looting a food warehouse owned by a businessman with army connections was fired on by a private security guard, injuring seven.
notes: Coded as a 0 for repression because security guard was private

issuenote: Mobs ransacked warehouses of sugar, and Haitian police fired tear gas to clear them out of one building.
Haitians pelted rocks and broken bottles from a store rooftop to protect it from looters.
A man was attacked and stabbed by a mob who accused him of being a pro-army militiamen.

target1: Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti headquarters
issuenote: Haitians overran FRAPH headquarters and destroyed telephones and other property.
Aristide supporters protested against the military.
notes: Event occurred near Port-Au-Prince, but exact location not specified; coded as Port-Au-Prince

issuenote: A warehouse owner who felt threatened fired into a crowd, killing one and injuring four.
About half a dozen pro-military attaches hacked a bus driver to death.
About 5,000 pro-democracy Haitians marched to army headquarters demanding that Cedras step down and also leave Haiti.
Several thousand people demonstrated in support of Aristide; a paramilitary member threw a rock at demonstrators, who then seized him, beat him, and turned him over to U.S. forces.
A pro-democracy rally was broken up by plainclothes Haitians who drove through in a truck and mowed down at least 15 people.
notes: Repress coded as 0 because it is believed that the bus that drove through the demonstration killed people accidently

issuenote: About 15 men attacked pro-Aristide artist and democratic activist Stevenson Magloire and beat him to death.
Marcellus Denis, an Aristide supporter, was forced to eat pictures of Aristide and was beaten, tortured and had several bones broken and later died.
notes: Event date estimated

issuenote: A pro-Aristide march had a bus plow through it being driven by a pro-military militiaman, killing 24 people and wounding at least 15 others.
notes: Some disparity in total killed, so most recent number coded
geo_comments: Located about 60 miles southwest of the capital.

issuenote: A police force trainee swearing in was broken up by about 500 people who accused the inductees of being linked to the military and forced them to flee.
A protest was held against Cedras, and a shot was fired by a U.S. troop after a Haitian smashed a bottle on the windshield of the general's departing car.
Rock-throwing demonstrators advanced on military headquarters to protest the alleged deaths of prisoners at the hands of Haitians soldiers.
People marched past army headquarters with pictures of Aristide.
Haitians waved branches and played musical instruments outside Cedras' mansion and marched to the airport to celebrate his departure from Haiti.
A police station was pillaged and U.S. troops prevented the lynching of Corporal Mondelus Norelus, a notorious torturer.
notes: Exact event date not given, so date of article coded as start and end date

issuenote: People raided the local police station, chased off a half-dozen policemen, stripping one of his clothes, and pounded the police station to the ground with sledgehammers.

target1: Front for the Advancement and Progress of  Haiti members
issuenote: Vigilantes went from house to house looking for FRAPH members, found a member's house and bloodied his wife's face, then killed a man with a machete outside, then went back to the FRAPH member's house and killed him.
notes: Coded as issue1 10 because Lavalas was looking for a FRAPH member that committed human rights abuses

issuenote: A pro-Aristide crowd rioted.
notes: Coded as single event because there seems to be momentum

issuenote: A voodoo priest and another person were killed and at least ten houses and five stores linked to members of the military were set on fire and a grain depot was looted.
notes: Coded as a separate event from attack on lottery kiosk on same day because this event occurred about 100 miles away from Port-Au-Prince

issuenote: Haitians beat up an army-linked gunman.
notes: Very little information given about event

actor2: Front for the Advancement and Progress of Haiti militants
issuenote: A rural police chief, with the help of FRAPH, broke up a planned pro-Aristide celebration, and arrested four members of a peasants organization.
Bus drivers on the route between Port-Au-Prince and the town of Jacmel went on strike to protest new government-set fares which they said were too low to cover their expenses.
notes: Start and end date of strike not specified, so date of article coded as start and end date

issuenote: Bus drivers on the route between Port-Au-Prince and the town of Jacmel, went on strike to protest new government-set fares which they said were too low to cover their expenses.
notes: Start and end date of strike not specified, so date of article coded as start and end date

issuenote: A Haitian warrant officer was stabbed by two men; it is believed the two men had political motivations for the attack.
notes: Event date not specified, first of month coded as start and end date

issuenote: Deputy mayor Cadet Damzal was beheaded by men with machetes, who attacked him as he walked home.
notes: Coded as an etype 8 because local political figure target of violence and paramilitary group is believed to be behind the attack

issuenote: A crowd accused police officers of committing human rights abuses and mobbed their patrol vehicle.
About 2,000 students who failed their high school exams and who were angry about fraud in the grading system ransacked the Education Ministry.
Members of the Haitian Women's Solidarity association demonstrated to protest rapes and other violence they experienced during Haiti's three-year period of military rule.
Hundreds of discharged soldiers massed at army headquarters demanding their salary for December and payment of pensions.
notes: Exact dates of event not given, an approximate start and end date was assigned

issuenote: Discharged soldiers rioted then protested against the military.
About 1,500 protesters marched around the Presidential Palace, demanding that Haiti's army be disbanded; scores of demonstrators later broke into the Ministry of Commerce.
A demonstration was called to protest the Justice Minister's loyalty to past military-backed governments.
notes: Event date not specified, an approximated start and end date were assigned

issuenote: Reporters held a demonstration to protest that they were being turned into propaganda machines that were ''mouthpieces for only one man,'' meaning Aristide.
notes: Event date not specified, so start and end date were approximated

issuenote: Law enforcement volunteers angry at having failed entry tests for a new police academy ransacked a police station, beat up an officer and burned him and stole weapons.
Prisoners angry about delays in the judicial process threw rocks and set fires, with at least 6 prisoners being injured.
Carnival children protested against Jimmy Carter.

Cannibal Army supporters set fire to a customs house, police station and a state-run insurance company and later stormed the internal revenue bureau, carted out documents and burned them in revenge for his death.
Officers stormed a slum to arrest several supporters of street gang leader Amiot Metayer; during the raid, bystanders were shot at and at least five people were killed.
notes: Police deny shooting at bystanders, but several witnesses say that police fired on bystanders; unsure how many of the five that were killed were bystanders

issuenote: About 100 opposition supporters went into the streets to protest Aristide's government.
About 1,000 Aristide supporters held a demonstration.
More than a thousand mourners at a funeral for slain gang leader Amiot Metayer hurled rocks at police.
A two-day strike was called by the North District Front to protest against Aristide.
Anti-government protesters demonstrated and smashed the windows of vehicles with rocks, demanding Aristide's resignation; one person was shot in clashes with police.
Anti-government protesters demonstrated and some protesters threw rocks at police and police fired tear gas to disperse the protesters.
Hundreds of anti-government protesters demonstrated to demand the ouster of Aristide and police and protesters exchanged gunfire, with one protester being shot in the head and a police officer shot.

A protest of 100 anti-government demonstrators was broken up by police using clubs; after police broke up the march, the protesters began marching again and a man threw rocks at the protesters who threw rocks back.
The Gonaives Resistance Front held an anti-government demonstration.
Police shot and killed a 21-year-old man, Edner Morency, as he was carrying an empty bucket to fetch water.
notes: Not known if victim was linked to protests in Gonaives

issuenote: 100 Aristide supporters threw rocks and bottles at 20 opposition activists who were getting ready for a protest march and Aristide partisans pushed and shoved the opposition protesters.
Aristide supporters held a pro-government protest.
notes: Difficult to determine if this protest is part of earlier event on same day or separate

issuenote: Gunmen opened fire on a Radio Maxima vehicle headed to Cap-Haitien Airport to pick up Mischa Gaillard, an opposition politician.
Aristide partisans blocked opposition supporters from entering Cap-Haitien to join the third day of talks aimed at discussing national strategies to force Aristide's resignation.
Aristide partisans threw stones and rocks at passing vehicles on in an effort to clear the streets and prevent anti-government protests.
Gunmen shot activist Ali Perard, 28, in the right leg as he was leaving the opposition talks.
Gunmen plundered the home of Front spokesman Eliscar Charles.
Followers of slain strongman Amiot Metayer launched an attack in which three officers were injured with gunshot wounds; a girl nearby was hit by a stray bullet and killed.
On a hunt for Amiot Metayer's followers, police raided the Raboteau slum and burned houses after they swept the area; two people were killed and twelve of Metayer's followers were arrested.
Five men opened fire on Radio Caraibes, damaging the sports director's car and the office faÁade.
Aristide supporters prevented a protest against environmental degradation, and they punched demonstrators and tore out of their hands the saplings they intended to plant.
50 women's rights activists protested the deaths of two women allegedly shot and killed by police, and their demonstration was broken up by about 30 Aristide supporters who threw rocks.
Gang member Wilson Lemaire was shot and killed by a rival gang.
Hundreds of Amiot Metayer supporters demonstrated, accusing Cite Soleil Mayor Fritz Joseph of having sent a rival to kill Wilson Lemaire.
Police broke up a demonstration.
notes: Very little information

issuenote: Government opponents set fire to a pro-government radio station, Radio Pyramide, gutting the building.
University students and opposition activists held a protest against the government.
A planned opposition protest was broken up by 8,000 Aristide supporters, Aristide and opposition supporters began throwing rocks at each other and police fired tear gas and arrested 30.
notes: Difficult to determine if protest actually started before violence broke out or if it was unable to start; cautiously coded as an escalation from an etype 1 to an etype 4

issuenote: 184 different civil groups called a one-day general strike to protest police breaking up a protest on November 14.
notes: Strike call was only partly adhered to; also, strike was meant to be nationwide, but most people did not hear about it and it seems confined to Port-Au-Prince and Cap-Haitien

issuenote: 184 different civil groups called a one-day general strike to protest police breaking up a protest on November 14.
notes: Strike call was only partly adhered to; also, strike was meant to be nationwide, but most people did not hear about it and it seems confined to Port-Au-Prince and Cap-Haitien

issuenote: Jean-Robert Lalane, an opposition leader, was shot in the shoulder by one of two gunmen who scaled a wall at his home.
A man's severed head was found with leaflets threatening some 70 opposition figures and journalists.
notes: Coded as an etype 9 because it is not clear if assailants were acting with the support of the government; also, date head was found coded as start and end date

issuenote: Members of nine different civil groups occupied the conference room in the Organization of American State's main office, saying they won't leave until the organization intervenes and the government releases detained protesters.

Students demanding Aristide resign and the release of two detained business leaders were pelted with rocks by Aristide supporters and were splashed with poison ivy-spiked water and police used billy clubs on some.
Government opponents gathered to mark the deaths of three students shot to death by the Haitian army during an anti-government rally and clashed with police; shots rang out and one person was killed.
notes: Coded as a 0 for repress because it is unclear who fired the shots that killed a bystander

issuenote: About 100 students demanding that Aristide resign clashed with government supporters; rocks were thrown, and students ransacked two university buildings, injuring at least 14 people.
notes: A lot of things going on, coded as same event because there is momentum

issuenote: An anti-government demonstration was held, and two children were shot and wounded.
notes: Very little information; coded as 0 for repression because it is not specified who fired the shots

issuenote: Hundreds of students and others protested, calling for Aristide to resign and police fired tear gas, shots were fired and three people were killed in clashes with police.
notes: Coded as a 1 for repression because it is not clear who fired the shots

issuenote: Three people were killed when an anti-government demonstration led to clashes with police and Aristide supporters.
notes: Coded as a 1 for repression because it is not clear who fired the shots

issuenote: Thousands of university students over three days chanted anti-Aristide slogans and Aristide supporters shot at them, and police fired tear gas and shot in the air.
notes: Very difficult to tell if student-led protests are separate from other anti-government protests during same time period in Port-Au-Prince

issuenote: More than 1,000 Aristide supporters demonstrated and threw rocks and shot at anti-government protesters, injuring three and also harassed drivers; police fired tear gas and shots in the air.
One person was killed by gunfire from a vehicle carrying armed men.
notes: Very little information

issuenote: Aristide supporters broke into a national police arms locker, loading their vehicles with weapons.
A demonstration was held calling for President Aristide to step down.
notes: Very little information

issuenote: Thousands of protesters demanding the ouster of Aristide had rocks thrown at them by Aristide supporters and were also shot at, with three people being injured and police fired shots and tear gas.
notes: Very difficult to tell if student-led protests are separate from other anti-government protests during same time period in Port-Au-Prince

issuenote: Students demonstrated calling for Aristide to step down, and police fired tear gas and arrested three.
A strike was held to protest against the Aristide government.
notes: Strike call was only partly adhered to

issuenote: Thousands of Aristide supporters held a demonstration.
At least three gas stations that closed during the anti-government strike on December 16 were vandalized.
notes: Coded as an etype 3 because targets were selected based on their participation in strike

issuenote: Several hundred anti-government protesters had tear gas fired at them by police and several were arrested; at least 3 were shot and wounded by Aristide supporters.
An anti-government protest was held.
notes: Very little information

issuenote: An anti-government protest was held.
notes: Very little information

issuenote: An anti-government protest was held.
notes: Very little information

issuenote: An anti-government protest was held and police killed a teenage boy; protesters then torched several government buildings.
Gunmen occupied the house of lead singers of the Haitian roots music group Boukman Eksperyans, which has been critical of Aristide's government.
More than 10,000 people took part in an anti-government demonstration, and gunmen drove by in a truck and shot at the protesters, and one or two people were killed and police returned fire.
notes: Coded as a 1 for repression because it is not clear whose shots killed the victims

issuenote: Several thousand Aristide supporters held a demonstration in front of the National Palace.
During an anti-government protests, eight people were killed by Aristide supporters.
notes: Very little information

actor1: Coalition of musicians, painters and writers
issuenote: More than 1,000 musicians held a free concert calling for President Aristide's resignation while artists painted rainbows over pro-government graffiti.
notes: Coded as an etype 1 because article says demonstration was organized by a coalition of artists

issuenote: About 2,000 medical students and doctors and others protested against the Aristide government.
University students organized a protest of thousands against the Aristide government.
More than 1,000 Aristide supporters demonstrated in front of the National Palace, and occupants of a van opened fire on the crowd, killing two people and injuring six.
A protest march against President Aristide with dozens of people was held, and police arrested Eliscar Charles, allegedly for organizing an illegal demonstration.
Thousands of Aristide supporters held a demonstration.

actor1: Platform of Civil Society Associations and Opposition Parties
issuenote: An anti-government protest was held and police fired tear gas and shot two people; the protesters later re-grouped and were broken up again and a gunfight broke out.
notes: Coded as an escalation to an etype 8 because police who were breaking up the protest were fired on by Aristide supporters

issuenote: Clashes between supporters and opponents of Aristide.
notes: Unclear if police or protesters fired shots

issuenote: An anti-government protest led to clashes, with shots being fired.
notes: Unclear if police or protesters fired shots

issuenote: Members of the anti-government Artibonite Revolutionary Resistance Front engaged in a shootout with police, and one Front member was shot and killed.
Businessman Claude Bernard Lauture was kidnapped and his body was found at the morgue on January 10.

Thousands of opposition protesters clashed with Aristide supporters, and one student was shot and killed by Aristide supporters and police used batons on the protesters and shot and killed an Aristide supporter.
Armed thugs stormed the state university hospital demanding to see who had joined anti-government protests.
Government opponents burned two houses, including the home of the pro-Aristide deputy mayor, but no one was injured.
A two-day general strike was called in an attempt to force President Aristide out of office.
notes: Strike was not widely adhered to in Cap-Haitien

issuenote: A two-day general strike was called in an attempt to force President Aristide out of office.
notes: Strike was not widely adhered to in Cap-Haitien

notes: Strike was not widely adhered to in Cap-Haitien

issuenote: Tens of thousands of people participated in an anti-government demonstration, and Aristide partisans threw sticks at the marchers at one point.
An Aristide supporter was shot and killed during rival pro and anti-government demonstrations.
notes: Coded as an escalation from an etype 2 to an etype 9 because protester was killed during rival demonstrations

issuenote: Pro-Aristide protesters set an anti-government activist on fire in retaliation for the killing of an Aristide protester on the same day.
notes: Coded as an escalation from an etype 2 to an etype 4 because protester was killed during rival demonstrations

issuenote: Students held an anti-government demonstration.
notes: Very little information

issuenote: A group of vandals with sledgehammers tied up guards and began attacking antennas, forcing at least seven radio stations and one television station off the air.
A local district attorney's home was burned down, and two pro-government radio stations Radio Pyramide and Radio America that were located in his home were destroyed.
Hundreds of students protesting the death of an anti-government activist had stones hurled at them by Aristide supporters, and police fired tear gas and bullets in the air.

4,000 people took part in a rally against Aristide, calling for him to resign and Aristide supporters threw rocks, breaking windows at Haiti's national television station and police repressed the event.
Masked attackers in a car shot two students leaving an anti-government protest.
notes: Coded as a separate event from protest on same day because students were leaving protest when shooting occurred

issuenote: An anti-government protest led one person to be shot and killed.
notes: Very little information; coded as 0 for repression because it is not specified who fired the shots and instead coded as an escalation to an etype 4

issuenote: Assailants torched two private community radio stations, presumably in retaliation for assaults on pro-government stations Radio Pyramide and Radio America.
200 students and teachers held a protest against Aristide, and police hit some of the students with clubs and fired tear gas and warning shots; students then threw stones at private schools.
The Arbonite Revolutionary Resistance Front fired on the Gonaives police station from a passing car and then approached on foot, spraying the building with bullets and two police officers' houses.
More than 20,000 Aristide supporters marched in a show of support for the president.
Police used tear gas and fired warning shots to prevent an anti-government protest by about 200 students and teachers at Port-au-Prince university and one was arrested.
A protest against Aristide by law school students was broken up by police who fired shots, with three people being injured.
Students attempting to hold an anti-government protest were forced to stay in the Medical School's courtyard or in front of the building, where riot police cordoned them off.
5,000 demonstrators demanded that Aristide stay in power for his full term, and police used tear gas to to keep the government supporters away from opposition supporters.
Shooting broke out between police and armed militants from the Arbonite Revolutionary Resistance Front.
notes: Unclear who fired first; coded as an etype 8 with 1 for repression because police exchanged fire with militants

issuenote: Members of the Arbonite Revolutionary Resistance Front exchanged gunfire with police, and a taxi driver passing by was shot and killed.
notes: Unclear if police or militants fired shots first, coded as an etype 8 because the Artibonite Revolutionary Resistance Front seeks to drive Aristide from power

issuenote: Police arrested labor union members.
notes: Coded as an etype 7 because arrests seem politically motivated

issuenote: More than 400 students protested against the Aristide government, and after the protest they ran victory laps around a university building.

About 400 anti-government protesters held a demonstration.
Members of the anti-Aristide militant group Artibonite Revolutionary Resistance Front exchanged gunfire with police, and one passerby was killed.
notes: Unclear if police or militants fired shots first, coded as an etype 8 because the Artibonite Revolutionary Resistance Front seeks to drive Aristide from power

issuenote: The Arbonite Revolutionary Resistance Front threatened to execute three people accused of collaborating with police and shot each of them once in the foot.
A protest calling for Aristide's resignation was held, and 11 of the protesters were shot and wounded by pro-government militants.
At least 15,000 protesters called for Aristide's resignation.

About 15 students set a roadblock ablaze in front of the hospital to protest the death of a student protester and stoned police and police arrested all of them and fired shots in the air.

100 union activists gathered in front of the U.N. office to protest the arrest of 12 union members for allegedly trying to overthrow the government and the protesters demanded that international institutions intervene.
At the wake of an Aristide partisan killed during a protest, a clash erupted between pro- and anti-government factions, and a policemen who tried to intervene was shot and killed.
notes: Coded as an escalation to an etype 9 because killing of policemen seems closely linked to incident at funeral and not politically motivated

issuenote: Opposition protesters were attacked by Aristide supporters, who fired shots and threw rocks and bottles at them, injuring several.
Tens of thousands of government opponents marched to demand Aristide's resignation.
An anti-government protest was held, and one protester was reported killed and about 10 were wounded in unclear circumstances, and police fired shots in the air to disperse the protest.
notes: Coded as a 0 for repression because police fired shots in the air and did not use tear gas or any other form of repression to stop the protest; coded as an escalation from an etype 2 to an etype 4 because the event turned violent but it is not

issuenote: About 100 students set up flaming tire barricades and threw stones, and police fired tear gas to disperse them.
notes: Not clear if a protest was held that turned violent or if rock throwing was all that transpired; coded as an etype 4

issuenote: Hundreds of people rallied outside the National Palace in support of President Aristide.
Hundreds of people looted guns and helmets and a police car from the police station that was set on fire the previous day and also looted gates and bars from the local jail.
An anti-government demonstration was held.
Police arrested human rights activist Ketly Julien and three of her colleagues, accusing them of plotting a coup.
notes: Included because arrests seem politically motivated

issuenote: An anti-government march was held, and one student was shot and wounded by gunmen and police fired tear gas to break up the protest.
A police station was taken over by armed men.
notes: Very little information

issuenote: The homes of Aristide supporters were pillaged.
notes: Very little information

issuenote: Thousands of protesters marched vowing to repel any attempt to retake the city.
Government supporters marched to mark the third anniversary of Aristide's second inauguration.
People threw rocks at police and street battles occurred between the Gonaives Resistance Front and police, with between three and seven police killed and a couple of other people also killed.

issuenote: Armed Aristide opponents seized the police station, firing into the air and chasing away police and also burning down the courthouse; two people were killed.

notes: Event date not specified, so date of article coded as start and end date

Opposition supporters demonstrated, demanding that Aristide and his followers be put on trial; towards the end of the protest, Aristide supporters began firing on the protesters, killing at least 6 people.

Loyalists demanding the return of President Aristide set up flaming barricades and stoned cars.
A protest was held against the government and United States and police used tear gas and a shootout occured between police and protesters and two people were killed; after this, crowds rampaged.

Two gangs exchanged gunfire after arguing over a shipment of donated rice and flour, with three people being injured.
dozens of young men demonstrated, demanding Aristide's return and the departure of a U.S.-led international peacekeeping force.
A strike was called at the port in Port-Au-Prince.

issuenote: During a funeral procession for five slain men, several police officers opened fire on mourners, injuring five.

Aristide supporters held a demonstration against the government and U.S.

notes: Very little information
geo_comments: Location is a slum southwest of the capital.

issuenote: A protest calling for Aristide's return turned violent and protesters killed three policemen and kidnapped a fourth; the protesters looted shops and exchanged gunfire with security guards and shouted "Down with Bush!"; 7 were killed.
A peaceful pro-Aristide demonstration was fired on by police, killing two young men.
A pro-Aristide protester was shot dead.
notes: Coded as an escalation to an etype 9 because there is no information about who fired shots or why; there is very little information about this event

issuenote: At least five men were killed by gunmen outside the home of an anti-Aristide community leader.
geo_comments: Location is a slum southwest of the capital.

issuenote: About 150 Aristide supporters, some with machetes and guns, staged a protest demanding Aristide's return; they blocked roads using torched cars.
Stone-throwing crowds attacked Catholic Relief Services  workers as they prepared to distribute food.

100 protesters shouted insults at Haiti's interim Prime Minister and President, accusing them of not doing enough to help flood victims in Gonaives and threw rocks at cars carrying their guards and police fired shots injuring 2.
Civilians fired shots in the air and smashed rocks into a vehicle carrying people from Doctors Without Borders and at an Oxfam truck and stole bottled water.
A group of men looted clothes and bed sheets from a United Nations base.
Gang members torched 20 houses and killed 2 people in retaliation for a man that was killed.
Men ran through the streets, firing gunshots into the air and burning cars along the road.
notes: Coded as issue1 10 because these men seem to have been Aristide supporters

issuenote: Business leaders called for a "day of protest against terrorism," and many banks, stores and gas stations were closed.
A few hundred supporters of Aristide's Lavalas Family party staged a peaceful demonstration.
People looted a truckload of relief supplies and made off with mattresses, shovels, sacks of flour and boxes of medicine.
Unidentified arsonists also set two vehicles on fire.

Gunmen held up one Tele Haiti pickup and doused it with gasoline, but then couldn't find matches; as the driver tried to drive away, his windshield was smashed by rocks; another journalists car was shot at.
A police officer was shot and killed by an armed group.
notes: Very little information

issuenote: Gunmen  arrived in five vehicles and raided a building and executed between 13 people, most of whom were students.
notes: Coded as an etype 9 because event seems to have been carried out by a non-state organization; if police were involved, it was not with the consent of the government and so it cannot be an etype 7

issuenote: A three day general strike was called by Aristide supporters to demand the release of Aristide supporters who have been arrested.
notes: Strike call was largely ignored by the population

issuenote: Men in black uniforms arrived in a police vehicle, dragged men outside, made them lie face down on the ground and shot them in the back of the head.
notes: Coded as an etype 9 because it is not clear if assailants were acting with the support of the government; it is also not clear if assailants were actually members of the police or if they were part of some other armed group

issuenote: About 30 people held a demonstration for peace.
Police chief Dieufrene Louis died when unknown gunmen opened fire.
notes: Very little information

issuenote: Armed group fired on a police station  after the arrest of gang members; peacekeepers thought that rebels called by police had come to attack and took their guns and when rebel supporters heard more than 100 people looted.
Gunmen ran through the streets firing into the air and setting cars on fire and killed a civilian who worked for the police department and tried to set his body on fire.
Gunmen shot into the air and torched at least nine cars.
More than 100 of former soldiers tried to occupy their former headquarters near the National Palace.
A group of armed men hijacked a bus carrying 11 off-duty peacekeepers and beat them before letting them go.
Outside a women's prison, four cars were set on fire.
Supporters of a rebel wanted for homicide burned tires and threw rocks at passers-by.
Several hundred Aristide supporters marched, calling for peace and the return of Aristide from exile.
Seven prisoners died and four police officers were wounded when inmates set fire to part of the national prison in an attempt to break free.
notes: Coded a 0 for repression because the slain inmates were killed by other prisoners for refusing to go along with their escape plan

issuenote: Unknown assailants opened fire on a police station, injuring three officers.
About 15 gunmen opened fire in a marketplace and set fire to merchandise; one person was injured.
A few dozen men marched to protest a major U.N. operation aimed at rooting out pro-Aristide gang members.
75 public doctors and 65 interns staged a strike to protest overdue pay and to protest a Health Ministry decision to accept private school students in the residency program.
notes: Start and end date of strike approximated

issuenote: Protesters demanded that the government fulfill promises made in October to rebuild Gonaives.
A crowd of people at a food distribution site threw rocks at peacekeepers, and the peacekeepers fired tear gas into the crowd.
notes: Coded as a 0 for repression because it was not a domestic policing agent that fired the tear gas

issuenote: Two reporters were beaten and robbed after covering a UN operation; the attackers left a message on one of the reporter's tape recorders telling them not to come back.
notes: Included because crime does not seem to have been the motive of the attack

issuenote: Five policemen were kidnapped and later released with the aim of negotiating the release of a former military officer arrested by police.
Former soldiers wearing military uniforms killed 4 police officers while they were on patrol and stole two machine guns, four shotguns and a radio.
notes: Included because attack may have been politically motivated

issuenote: Armed gunmen attacked Haiti's national prison, killing one guard in a shootout and sparking a riot in which 500 prisoners escaped in an attempt to release drug traffickers.
About 500 people marched through two areas of Port-Au-Prince to demand the return of Aristide.
Three houses were torched and at least 20 people injured by gunshots in response to youths who had set up barricades to prevent crime.
Dozens of young men burned tires and threw rocks at peacekeepers, accusing them of standing by while Haitian police shot and killed two men.
Residents stoned a U.N. vehicle and fired on them, slightly wounding two and other peacekeepers were also shot at and injured.
notes: Very little information about other shootings; coded as an escalation to an etype 8

issuenote: A man was captured and burned alive by residents, who accused him of being a hired gun.
notes: Event date not specified; date of article coded as start and end date

issuenote: A pro-Aristide and anti-President Bush march of about 2,000 people was broken up by police, who fired tear gas and shot and killed at least 2 protesters and injuring 10.
More than 2,000 Aristide supporters staged a peaceful demonstration, accusing police of killing two men during a recent protest.
Thousands of Aristide supporters, including many women claiming that police had killed their sons, marched to protest alleged police killings.
About 150 Aristide supporters protested, demanding the release of Aristide loyalists.
A one-day general strike was called to protest the interim government's failure to counter a surge in violence.
Peacekeepers raiding a police station held by former soldiers were fired on and fired back; one peacekeeper and two former soldiers were killed; in another incident, a peacekeeper was killed.
notes: Coded as same event because actors and targets are the same

issuenote: Peacekeepers raiding a police station held by former soldiers were fired on and fired back; one peacekeeper and two former soldiers were killed; in another incident, a peacekeeper was killed.
notes: Coded as same event because actors and targets are the same

issuenote: A group of gunmen fired several times at Justice Minister Bernard Gousse's house, killing a policeman who was standing guard.
Thousands of Aristide supporters held a rally calling for his return and shots were fired by an anti-Aristide street gang; later, police fired on the protesters and killed at least one.
Someone threw a grenade into the compound of Haiti's electoral office, slightly damaging the structure.
Gunmen with assault rifles ambushed and shot and killed two policemen and their driver in an official government car and burned the bodies after killing them.
Several thousand protesters demanded Aristide's return, doused a life-size effigy of interim Prime Minister Latortue with gasoline and set it ablaze outside a church.
Two gunmen riding in the back of a pickup truck opened fire on electoral offices, hitting an electricity transformer.
Several people were killed in clashes between rival gangs.
Armed men fired at a car carrying an American freelance photographer and her driver but no one was injured.
Unknown assailants shot at a soldier guarding the U.N.'s new headquarters; he escaped injury because the bullets hit him in his helmet and vest.
People looted an abandoned truck of soda, and onlookers then mobbed the looters, trying to pull soda bottles out of the boxes for themselves.
Hundreds of protesters demanded the return of Aristide and blamed the U.S.-backed interim government and U.N peacekeepers for the dire state of life in Cite Soleil.
An off-duty police officer was beheaded and set on fire.
notes: Event date not specified, so date of article coded as start and end date

issuenote: A pro-Aristide gang clashed with peacekeepers, and a young bystander was killed.
A crowd of mourners danced and chanted protest songs and political organizers moved through the crowd calling for more jobs and food in the slum.
A UN peacekeeper from the Philippines was shot in the head and killed when an unknown number of armed gunmen opened fire.
Armed gangs trapped a group of U.N. civilian police behind a flaming barricade and disabled their armored personnel carrier in a two-hour gunbattle.
Protesters demanding the release of Aristide loyalists were fired on by police, killing five; after the shooting some protesters fled to a slum, where two cars were set on fire.
Haitian police, escorted by U.N. peacekeepers, charged into Bel Air slum and started chasing and beating residents; one man was shot and killed after being chased by police.
notes: Coded as an etype 7 because violence by police was unprovoked and victims were not involved in any crime-related incident

issuenote: More than 5,000 supporters of ousted President Aristide marched to demand his return from exile, with one protester reportedly shot and killed by police.

A market was burned down by arsonists and gunmen opened fire, killing two people and at least eight others who were burned; a police station was attacked and four policemen were injured and two people arrested.
Haitian police shot and killed at least four people and burned 12 homes during raids to root out gang members.
notes: Coded as an etype 7 because this seems like more than policing crime due to the excessive violence that was employed

issuenote: Gunmen opened fire on U.N. troops at a checkpoint, wounding two peacekeepers and two Haitian Red Cross workers.
Peruvian U.N. soldiers were patrolling in an armored vehicle when they came under fire from armed gunmen; two peacekeepers were injured in the attack.
notes: Coded as an etype 8 because peacekeepers are acting on behalf of the Haitian government in their peacekeeping operation

issuenote: Gang members attacked a U.N. military position, and peacekeepers fired back, killing one gang member.
notes: Coded as an etype 8 because peacekeepers are acting on behalf of the Haitian government in their peacekeeping operation

issuenote: Bus and taxi drivers went on strike to protest high gas prices.
notes: End date of strike not specified, date of article coded as start and end date

issuenote: Police fired indiscriminately during an anti-gang operation; at least two people were killed; police then stood by as men in civilian clothes attacked and lynched three suspected gang members.
More than a dozen police seeking gang members aligned with Aristide stormed a soccer game; other police and civilians surrounded the stadium, shooting and hacking people with machetes.
A police officer that intended to arrest two other policemen suspected of corruption was kidnapped; it is believed the police officers he was going to arrest kidnapped him.
notes: Coded as an etype 10 because both actor and target were members of the police; also, it is unclear what happened to the kidnapped policemen because no other information is provided

issuenote: 20 young men and women hurled rocks and shouted insults at the motorcade of presidential candidate Dumarsais Simeus and a shot was fired.
More than 10,000 protesters demonstrated in support of former President Preval's bid to regain the presidency and called for the release of political prisoners and the return of Aristide.
Armed groups using children as human shields fired at UN troops; over a period of three days of shooting, one UN soldier was injured.
notes: Coded as an etype 8 because peacekeepers are acting on behalf of the Haitian government in their peacekeeping operation

issuenote: Hundreds of protesters threw rocks and burned tires to protest the treatment of Haitian migrants in the Dominican Republic and at least three people were shot and police fired tear gas.
Judges went on strike to protest the government's decision to remove judges from office.
notes: Start and end date of strike approximated

issuenote: Supreme Court judges fired by Haiti's interim government formed a human chain with law students and court clerks to block their replacements from being sworn in.
A retired Royal Canadian Mounted Policeman who traveled to Haiti to help peacekeepers was killed when gunmen fired on his vehicle.
notes: Coded as an etype 8 because peacekeepers are acting on behalf of the Haitian government in their peacekeeping operation

issuenote: A Jordanian peacekeeper was shot and killed while on patrol.
notes: Coded as an etype 8 because peacekeepers are acting on behalf of the Haitian government in their peacekeeping operation

actor1: Haitian Chamber of Commerce and Industry
issuenote: A one-day general strike was held to protest a recent wave of kidnappings and to pressure U.N. peacekeepers to move against gangs who are responsible.
Hundreds of people demonstrated to denounce violence after clashes between gangs and U.N. peacekeepers reportedly left one person dead the day before.
Several hundred people held a sit-in outside UN headquarters to demand improvements in public security.
Gumen shot and killed two peacekeepers and seriously wounded another at a security checkpoint.
notes: Coded as an etype 8 because peacekeepers are acting on behalf of the Haitian government in their peacekeeping operation

issuenote: Residents claimed that Jordanian peacekeepers sprayed a slum area of cinderblock homes with high-powered weapons in revenge for the killing of two Jordanian peacekeepers a few days earlier, killing four.
notes: Coded as an etype 9 because this attack was not supported by the government and seems like a group of rogue peacekeepers were responsible; this report was not confirmed by the UN but the evidence indicates that peacekeepers did in fact fire on

issuenote: About 300 protesters marched, accusing U.N. troops of shooting civilians and demanding polling sites for the February 7 elections.
Hundreds of people marched past a U.N. fort and made obscene gestures at Jordanian peacekeepers after two people were allegedly shot by peacekeepers earlier that day.

100 prisoners demanding their freedom rioted in Haiti's main prison; there were gunshots and two people were killed and unveiled a banner demanding justice.
notes: Coded as an etype 3 because the prisoners unveiled a banner and this implies that the riot was planned out

issuenote: Two armed gangs clashed over control of a generator to see the World Cup; six people were killed.
Gang members fired on a UN security checkpoint and exchanged gunfire; one youth was injured.
notes: Coded as an etype 8 because peacekeepers are acting on behalf of the Haitian government in their peacekeeping operation

issuenote: Arodon Bien-Aime, parlaiment's number-two secretary was shot several times by unknown assailants and injured.
Haitian truck drivers staged a two-month strike and threw rocks and reportedly fired shots at vehicles entering and leaving Haiti to protest Haiti's customs agency's raising of import taxes.
notes: Exact start and end date not known, an approximate start and end date was assigned

issuenote: At least 22 people were killed in fighting between rival gangs that lasted overnight.
An armed Haitian gang exchanged gunfire with peacekeepers, with three peacekeepers being injured and at least one gang member being shot and killed over three days.
notes: Coded as an etype 8 because peacekeepers are acting on behalf of the Haitian government in their peacekeeping operation

issuenote: Thousands of Aristide supporters held a protest march to demand the return of Aristide.
Over three days of gunfire exchanged between armed groups and peacekeepers after armed groups attacked UN security stations; 8 armed group members were killed.
notes: Coded as an etype 8 because peacekeepers are acting on behalf of the Haitian government in their peacekeeping operation

notes: Coded as an etype 8 because peacekeepers are acting on behalf of the Haitian government in their peacekeeping operation

issuenote: About 150 rape victims marched to demand justice and an end to discrimination against them.
Peacekeepers trying to remove debris from a road were fired on and fired back in self-defense; residents then threw rocks at peacekeepers and accused them of opening fire and killing two.
notes: Coded as a 2 for repression but it is not certain if peacekeepers fired the fatal shots

issuenote: Dozens of student demonstrators threw stones, broke UN vehicles' windshields, and burned a US flag.
Hundreds of protesters peacefully marched to demand the withdrawal of U.N. peacekeepers and the peacekeepers threw tear gas canisters to disperse the protesters.
Two Jordanian peacekeepers were shot and killed when they came under attack by gunmen.

100 students protested to demand the withdrawal of peacekeepers and a security guard opened fire injuring two people; protesters chased U.N. police officers and threw rocks and smashed the windshield of a U.N. vehicle.
notes: Coded as single event because there is momentum and the issue is the same

issuenote: Doctors and other hospital workers staged a strike to demand back wages.

issuenote: At least 4 people, including a police officer, were killed in incidents related to local elections.
Two polling stations were set on fire.
At least eight people were killed after a police officer's killing reignited a battle between the rival Grand Ravine and Ti Manchet gangs.
Striking workers removed the corpses of 11 infants from the morgue of the hospital and laid them out in a courtyard in a protest aimed at pressuring the government for back wages.
notes: Some of the actors involved in the protest were also participating in the two-week long Hospital strike, but this event seems like an event separate from the strike and not all strike participants took part in this event

issuenote: Several hundred people threw stones and clashed with police as they tried to move two men suspected of trying to kidnap a local child and police fired tear gas and UN police fired shots.
Hundreds of Aristide supporters demonstrated to protest UN operations and called for the return of Aristide from exile.
A freelance photographer was gunned down in his home by local gang members whom he had photographed during reporting assignments.
Clashes between armed gangs and peacekeepers led to the deaths of four gang members and several others were injured.
At least two peacekeepers were injured in exchanges with armed gangs and one passerby was killed in the cross-fire.
notes: Coded a 1 for repression because it is not clear who fired shots that killed passerby

issuenote: About 200 people staged a protest, calling for the withdrawal of UN peacekeepers.
A journalist with links to Aristide was shot and killed in his bed.
notes: Included in dataset because killing seems politically motivated and not driven by crime

issuenote: Alix Joseph, director of private Radio Provinciale, was ambushed by two assailants as he sat in a car and shot 11 times and killed.
notes: Included in dataset because killing seems politically motivated and not driven by crime

issuenote: Janitors and hospital support staff staged a strike to demand four weeks of back wages as well as ambulances and the rehiring of colleagues who recently lost their jobs.
Hundreds of people protested against the city government, accusing them of setting fire to a marketplace to remove them from the area.
More than 1,000 Aristide supporters marched to demand the return of Aristide.
Two men mistaken for kidnappers were beaten to death with rocks and sticks.
notes: Event date not specified, middle of month coded as start and end date

issuenote: People in a rural town seized and beat to death an accused rapist and murderer.
notes: Very little information; event date approximated

issuenote: Four people were bound, dragged from their homes and shot in the street and a fifth person was shot in his home in an apparent gang rivalry.
notes: Event date not specified, so date of article coded as start and end date

issuenote: A suspected kidnapper was stoned to death by a mob of people.
About 5,000 protesters marched to demand Aristide's return from exile and also criticized President Preval and the U.N. peacekeeping force.
