issuenote: A UN peacekeeper was dragged from a car and shot and peacekeepers fired tear gas and shots to disperse a crowd before recovering the body and two men were detained and several market stalls were set on fire.
About 25 Aristide supporters staged a protest calling for his return.
A small group of protesters threw rocks at police and peacekeepers.
Hundreds of armed former soldiers stormed an old barracks and prison to demand back pay and also to call for the government to bring back the army to provide security.
notes: Coded as an etype 1 because the protest was not violent and was highly organized by former soldiers

issuenote: Hundreds of people threw rocks to protest the high cost of living and peacekeepers fired tear gas to disperse them.
Several hundred people pushed and shoved to break down the door of a U.N. shelter.
A mob ambushed a truck carrying emergency food.
100 men rushed a school that collapsed to try to help with emergency relief efforts, and police and policekeepers drove them away with batons and riot shields and the men threw rocks.
300 voodoo priests marched, claiming foreign aid and the United Nations is holding back Haiti; the protesters also denounced the anniversary of Christopher Columbus' 1492 arrival.
Aristide supporters protested to demand the resignation of President Preval and threw rocks and bottles at police and police fired shots in the air to disperse them.
About 30 students set up flaming tire barricades and threw rocks at police to protest curriculum changes and police fired tear gas.
Students protesting for an improved curriculum barricaded themselves inside an administration building and smashed car windows with rocks and police fired tear gas and made arrests.
Education students torched a U.N. vehicle and threw bottles and rocks at police to protest the removal of math and science classes from the teaching school's curriculum.
Protesters clashed with police to prevent the seating of a local elections board.

Preval supporters smashed the windows of a vehicle carrying Union party supporter and a Haitian folk singer; police fired shots to disperse the crowd, beat attackers with rifle butts and detained several.
Hundreds of protesters raided polling places and dumped ballots in the streets.
150 demonstrators rioted, burned a makeshift dominican flag and tore down a sign at the Dominican embassy to protest the killing of a Haitian in the Dominican Republic.
300 students protesting curriculum changes and demanding a raising of the minimum wage and also that U.N. forces leave Haiti threw rocks at police and set a car on fire; police fired tear gas.
One person was killed in a clash between President Preval supporters and members of the Struggling People's Organization.
Students protesting curriculum changes, the minimum wage and the U.N. presence in Haiti attacked and burned a U.N. police vehicle and peacekeepers fired tear gas.

After a funeral for a priest, 2,000 Aristide supporters carried his coffin to the presidential palace to protest President Preval's policies and his failure to bring Aristide back from exile and rocks were thrown.
notes: Unclear which side killed victim

issuenote: Two groups of political supporters clashed and one person was killed.
Students protesting curriculum changes, the minimum wage and the U.N. presence in Haiti had tear gas thrown at them by police.
More than 2,000 people protested to demand an increase in Haiti's minimum wage; some of the protesters threw rocks at police and began ripping down flags of U.N. member countries.
Protesters demonstrated against a two-month electricity outage and threw rocks at peacekeepers; at least three people were injured.

Student protesters demanding  a hike in Haiti's minimum wage, changes in curriculum and the departure of the U.N. troops clashed with police and police entered the medical school campus and arrested 20.
Hundreds of Aristide supporters marched to demand officials reinstate their party in next year's legislative elections as well as the departure of President Preval and the return of Aristide.
Looters with machetes struck numerous shops and World Food Program warehouses as well as an Eagle Wings Foundation distribution center of various goods.
Barricades of burning tires, rubble and human corpses blocked the main road out of Port-Au-Prince as residents called for piles of putrid corpses to be removed.
Hundreds of prisoners, severely overcrowded and terrified by aftershocks, rioted and tried to escape; 12 to 19 prisoners were killed ten were killed and up to 40 were wounded by gunshots.
notes: Inmate deaths blamed on gangleader who shot inmates that refused to flee, but police likely were involved so coded a 2 for repression

issuenote: Armed group of about 20 men blockaded a street and attacked a food convoy and peacekeepers fired warning shots into the air to scare them off; Haitian police arrested 14 people suspected of participating in the attack.
Hundreds gathered at a gravel pit where countless earthquake victims had been dumped and called for the resignation of President Preval and the return of Aristide.
50 protesters gathered outside a temporary police headquarters building and chanted against Preval and against the fact that there is no food.
Small groups of state employees and lawyers held protests, denouncing President Preval's leadership.
notes: Not clear if this is a separate protest from other etype 2 on same day

issuenote: 300 protesters demonstrated outside the Petionville Mayor's office to demand food, water, work, and for their children to go back to school and also accused local officials of demanding bribes for donated food.
200 protesters marched toward the US embassy, crying out for food and aid.
About 200 people demonstrated to protest the lack of shelter.
About 100 people held a demonstration to protest against living in a camp and also to demand food.
More than 1,000 protesters demanded shelter.
More than 150 machete-wielding men attacked a World Food Program convoy and made off with food.
Evangelicals threw rocks at voodoo practitioners and urinated on voodoo symbols and destroyed altars and voodoo offerings of food and rum at a voodoo ceremony to conjure spirits to guide lost souls.
About 50 residents in a camp of earthquake victims protested to demand more tents.
A U.N. food convoy traveling from Gonaives to Dessalines was stopped and overrun by people, who looted two trucks before peacekeepers regained control.

A group of about 50 protesters demonstrated because they had not received sufficient relief supplies and were pushed back by baton-wielding police; some protesters were beaten and at least one was arrested.
About 100 protesters burned tires and an American flag to demand President Aristide's return.

Hundreds of high school students protested and hurled rocks at the Education ministry building to demand that their schools be cleared of homeless people so that classes can resume and police fired tear gas.
notes: End date of protests not specified; end date approximated

issuenote: Two Indian peasants who seized land after the Chiapas uprising are killed.
500 ranchers march through the streets to demand the government return to them land and livestock lost to Indian peasants during the Chiapas uprising.
2000 Indian peasants march through the streets, painting rebel slogans on the walls and staging a sit-in at city hall.
The PRI presidential candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio is assassinated by Mario Aburto Martinez.  Despite many conspiracy theories, a true motive is never learned.
Dozens of peasant and Indian groups caravan to Mexico City and then protest to show support for the EZLN rebels on the 75th anniversary of Emiliano Zapata's death, and to demand greater democracy.
Protesters block a highway to demand the ouster of a town mayor accused of embezzlement.
Cattlemen march in protest and also seize leader of Mexico's Southeastern Human Rights Association, accusing them of encouraging peasants to stage land invasions.
50 peasants occupy a major downtown intersection, demanding land reform and Indian rights.
Rebels kill an army soldier at a roadblock in the first violation of the ceasefire since the end of the Chiapas uprising.
9 Indian peasants are murdered.  Motive is unknown.
notes: Dates are estimated.

issuenote: The vice president of a large supermarket chain is abducted.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Unknown gunmen shoot and kill a Tijuana police chief and his bodyguard.
Hundreds of rock and bottle throwing squatters clash with police.
300 Indian peasants block a highway and set a police car on fire.
Hundreds of protesting farm workers camp downtown to demand that the government cease repression of farm workers.
A powerful car bomb explodes outside a luxury hotel.  The incident is linked to a dispute between rival drug gangs.
Student supporters of the PRD throw eggs at the PAN candidate.
As many as 150,000 people pour into the streets to celebrate a World Cup victory, but skirmishes with police leave several dozen wounded and several dead.
Rival Indian groups fight a gun battle.
Gunmen ambush 25 policemen investigating a wage of assaults.
Four men are killed in drug related violence.  Police say there could be a link to an arson fire that destroyed a car in the San Diego suburb of Chula Vista.
Gunmen assassinate the secretary general of the PRI.  Several different persons are convicted, but some of these convictions are overturned.
About 130 Chiapas ranchers and small farmers maintain a sit-in hunger strike, demanding the government end the rebellion.

400 peasants block several major highways, demanding the government fulfill promises to build health clinics, promote cattle ranching, and build roads.  Another group protests high electricity prices.
Peasants hold demonstrations in honor of the 1910 Mexican Revolution and to show support for the EZLN.  Protests escalate to riots, and police use tear gas.

actor1: State Council of Indigenous and Peasant Organizations
issuenote: Ethnic Maya peasants clash with police to show support for a local newspaper editor and former gubernatorial candidate.
A protest caravan makes its way to Mexico City to protest the loss of PRD candidate in Tabasco's gubernatorial election.
10,000 protesters march to demand the ouster of newly inaugurated president Ernesto Zedillo.  Some clash with riot police.
Hundreds of farmers ride their tractors into the main square to call for a nationwide moratorium on payments of past-due agricultural loans.

3000 Indian peasants protest the inauguration of a PRI governor in their state.  They then inaugurate their own governor, representing the PRD.
PRD supporters protest against an election result by blockading state oil drilling sites.
EZLN rebels break a cease fire and occupy a town, ransacking the town hall and burning government archives.  Government troops enter town and make a show of force, re-occupying the town.
30,000 people protest over an economic crisis, which led to a massive devaluation in the peso.
Violent protests erupt as peasants demand that the PRD candidate for governor, who lost an election, be installed into that office.
Violent protests erupt as peasants demand that the PRD candidate for governor, who lost an election, be installed into that office.
500 well-dressed demonstrators march on the presidential palace to protest austerity measures.

Thousands of PRI supporters block highways to protest reports that their governor was being forced to resign in favor of a candidate from the PRD, claiming it was their candidate who won an election. The protests escalate to rioting.
Mexican army and EZLN rebels clash.
Tens of thousands of PRD supporters protest against the president's policies toward the Zapatistas.
Thousands stage an anti-war protest in support of a peaceful solution to the Chiapas conflict.
A strike occurs at a copper mine somewhere in Mexico.

issuenote: Debtors surround the Interior Ministry to protest soaring interest rates.

Thousands of transport drivers protest government decision to declare a bus line insolvent and lay off its workers.  They also protest the arrest of the driver's union.
150,000 marchers protest the devalued peso, layoffs, high taxes and interest rate hikes associated with the Mexican financial crisis.
Hundreds of peasants blockade the stock market, led by the losing candidate in the prior year's gubernatorial race in Tabasco state.

target1: Peasant Organization of the Southern Sierra (OCSS)
issuenote: Farmers on their way to an OCSS protest to march against police brutality are shot dead by police.  The EPR is formed in response to this event.

Gunmen attack and rob a group of villagers.  Authorities blame a family feud.
Gunmen attack a police patrol.

Unemployed garbage collectors and laid-off bus drivers march against the ongoing economic crisis, demanding the government give their jobs back.
Thousands of stall owners march in response to rumors that the government will privatize public markets.
Hundreds of applicants rejected from National Autonomous University stage a building occupation.

Several thousand people rally on the anniversary of a 1968 student massacre.  The protest quickly turns into a rally about economic conditions; the protesters beat up two motorists and hijack and burn several buses.

Health workers stage a sit-in at health department offices to protest an incident where a gang of armed men robbed and raped three nurses working for a vaccination team.  They also protest against the health department.
300 protesters gather outside a courthouse as a rebel leader is arraigned.
Rifle carrying prison inmates riot, killing a social worker and wounding others.  They demand to be given armored cars for escape.
Angry residents of a village beat to death a man suspected of raping a local woman.
Protesters march against proposed changes to the social security system.
Protesters march against proposed changes to the social security system.
Protesters march against proposed changes to the social security system.
Students, unionists, and various organizations gather to protest a wave of privatizations and to show support for the Zapatistas.
Protesters rally against government handling of an air pollution emergency.
Protestors march through Mexico City, claiming the government has abandoned middle class debtors.
PRD supporters march against plans to privatize several oil wells and to demand compensation for environmental damage caused by oil operations.
PRD supporters march against plans to privatize several oil wells and to demand compensation for environmental damage caused by oil operations.
PRD supporters march against plans to privatize several oil wells and to demand compensation for environmental damage caused by oil operations.

Gunmen hijack a tourist bus, raping two Mexican girls and four foreign tourists.
15,000 people march to protest against the privatization of a petrochemical plant.
Indigenous Mexicans launch a hunger strike to prod the federal government to offer them social programs, aid, and farm land.
Over 100,000 protestors takes to the streets on May Day to protest against currency devaluation and unemployment.
Teachers protest for higher pay.  Police crack down violently.  The police chief is eventually fired for the incident.

Peasants free prisoners accused of participating in a nearby gun battle.

A former prosecutor is gunned down by uniformed men claiming to be federal agents.
Gunmen attack a bus containing American and Mexican peace activists.
A prison riot occurs.

issuenote: Workers at Chrysler plants across North America strike, affecting plants in Mexico, Michigan, and Indiana.
Protests occur across Mexico to honor Emiliano Zapata.  Protesters consist in Indians demonstrating over ethnic issues and land distribution.
Protesters rally outside the US embassy to protest a new immigration law.
Workers at Ford plants strike over a company announcement that there will be no profit-sharing this year after losses in 1996.
Workers at Ford plants strike over a company announcement that there will be no profit-sharing this year after losses in 1996.

Unknown gunmen kill a lawyer who reportedly mediated between army officers and drug traffickers.

Four men burst into a restaurant and kill six people, including two informants for the US DEA.
Indians in Chiapas protest the re-installation of a military camp.
Four people are killed in escalating drug violence.
8000 people gather to protest against violence in Juarez since the July 4 death of an area drug lord.
Gunmen kill four people in a nightclub in escalating drug violence.
Employees of two bus lines attack one another in an escalating conflict over routes and passengers.
Police initiate a series of drug raids in the Buenos Aires neighborhood.  Six people turn up dead, showing signs of torture.  19 elite police officers are eventually arrested.
Thousands of rebels and their supporters march from San Cristobal to Mexico City to press for greater Indian rights.
100 residents of the Buenos Aires neighborhood of Mexico City rally outside a police state to rally against police brutality.
A journalist is beaten as she steps off a bus for her coverage of gang violence.
PRI supporters and Zapatistas clash over land disputes and ethnic issues.
Students march to demand a full government accounting for a 1968 massacre of hundreds of peaceful demonstrators.  Several people are injured when marchers attack cars, buses, and loot stores.
A clash occurs between Zapatista and PRI supporters.  Authorities say it is an act of vengeance for a clash in May in the same village.
Workers at a small Korean owned auto parts factory stage a hunger strike against the local governor when he rejects their bid to form an independent union separate from government backed unions.
Thousands march against Columbus Day.  Mayan natives demand land and the fulfillment of government peace promises.

Unknown gunmen open fire on a journalist who wrote investigative pieces on the drug trade and official corruption.
20,000 people, many of them upper class, march to protest crime and police corruption.
More than 100 journalists march to demand an end to government corruption and violence against reporters orchestrated by drug traffickers.

About 70 gunmen loyal to a local faction of the PRI descend upon an Indian village, massacring Tzotzil Indians and members of an EZLN affiliated group called Las Abejas.  Many of the killers were political rivals.

4000 people march on the fourth anniversary of the Zapatista uprising and mourn the death of 45 people in Acteal.

Zapatista supporters protest against the Acteal massacre, and then clash with police in Ocosingo.  Police open fire, resulting in one death.
Zapatista supporters demand punishment for police officers who fired on demonstrators.
Zapatista supporters gather outside government office buildings and shout at soldiers on the day of a funeral for a woman shot dead at a protest.
Unknown gunmen kill 13 people, including an Egyptian diplomat, over the course of a week.
notes: Dates are estimated.

PRI supporters protest to demand that foreign human rights workers be expelled from Chiapas.
Prison inmates riot after a police sweep for weapons.
Conatram initiates a strike to demand that the government resolve a number of labor issues.
An enraged mob storms a court after a judge frees two kidnapping suspects on bail.  The mob beats the judge and lynches the accused kidnappers.
Thousands of crime victims and their supporters march to demand harsher punishments for criminals and corrupt police.

3000 Indians protest on the anniversary of Emiliano Zapata's death.  They demand democracy and land rights for Indians.
Zapatista activists staged a protest. Indian peasants build roadblocks in several areas.  Mexican army and police retake the area the next day.

issuenote: A mob of enraged villagers drags a man from his jail cell and hangs him after he was caught with a stolen pig and burro.
Prisoners angered by the transfer of their friends to other jails attack other prisoners.
Indian organizations march through Mexico City's Zocolo market to demand an end to second class status for Indians, better land distribution, and the removal of the military from Chiapas.
3000 Indian rebel sympathizers march to a town to protest the military deployment there.
Three members of a drug cartel are killed in a drive by shooting.
Gunmen fire seven shots into the car of a leader of the Mexico City assembly, the fifth such attack in recent months on leaders of the PRD.
Flight attendants strike against the national airline over working conditions, benefits, and salaries.
People (not rebels) take over parts of the town and deny the villagers the ability to choose political parties.  The government raids the town, firing tear gas and making arrests.
A mayoral candidate is assassinated.
Rebels claiming to fight for economic and social justice clash with military forces.
notes: The rebels are a breakaway faction of the EPR.

issuenote: EZLN rebels and the government clash in an Indian village after the rebels began setting up their own government.

ilocal: Road between Zihuatanejo and Ciudad Altamirano
issuenote: Gunmen ambush an army patrol.

Members of a leftist opposition party ambush ruling party supporters two days before gubernatorial elections.
Indian women march to protest the jailing of several Indian men.
PRI supporters riot after a court decision giving the mayoral race to an opposition party.  They loot the town hall.
Armed men attack a police and army patrol.
Three women beat to death an accused rapist they captured.
Prisoners riot when guards disobey orders and refuse to let hundreds of family members inside.  Inmates also protest against overcrowding and corruption.

actor1: Arellano Felix cartel / Tijunana cartel gunmen

Nine members of Greenpeace occupy the offices of the US state of Texas in Mexico City, protesting plans for a nuclear waste facility near the US-Mexico border.
9 members of Greenpeace stage a 24 hour take over of the Texas state offices in Mexico City, protesting against plans for a nuclear waste plant.
1000 people protest in front of the US embassy to protest against plans to build a nuclear waste facility in Texas.
More than 1000 protestors, many dressed in Indian costumes, march to protest Columbus Day and to demand indigenous rights.
Thousands protest plans to build a nuclear waste facility in Texas, only a few miles from the border.
Gunmen shot and killed 6 civilians.
Local officials are killed in an ambush attributed to the EPR.
Gunmen open fire on a family, killing five people in what authorities call a drug-related attack.
EPR rebels attack a police station and government store.
Heavily armed men ambush federal lawmen.
A land dispute between farmers erupts in violence.  Residents of Santo Domingo Teojomulco open fire on farmers from a rival town, San Lorenzo Texmelucan.
50,000 telephone workers stage a two hour walkout to protest a new 15 percent tax on telephone services.
Thousands camp outside the Congress to protest against the president's budget during a time of financial crisis.
EZLN and right wing paramilitaries clash.
Right wing paramilitaries and police descend on a township run by rebel sympathizers, forcing residents to flee to the mountains.

10 heavily armed prison inmates riot and attempt escape.
30 protesters camp outside the Monument of Independence, and then gather outside the stock exchange to demand changes in the government's policy in Chiapas.
notes: Start date is estimated.

issuenote: Members of Antorcha, a radical peasants organization that supports the PRI, camps out Mexico City's main plaza for more than a year.

issuenote: Unknown assailants open fire on a municipal jail.
Hundreds of ethnic Indian rebel supporters march to celebrate the anniversary of the Chiapas uprising.
Unknown assailants shoot guns and throw bombs into a house to intimidate the assistant police chief, but they accidentally kill him.

target1: National Coordinating Committee of Education Workers

Protesters gather to protest the deaths of immigrants trying to cross the US border.

target1: In law of the governor of Morales

Barefoot Tzotzil Indian women march in Acteal to demand peace in Chiapas.
Dozens of women march to demand police action against a wave of rapes and murders.
Thousands of students protest a tuition hike at National Autonomous University.
100,000 people march to protest against privatization of the country's electricity system.
Thousands of leftist party activists black streets in an effort to stop the inauguration of a new governor.

Thousands of students strike to protest tuition fees and take over about 40 schools throughout the UNAM university.  The students regularly stage massive demonstrations.  The strike eventually widens to include unionists and teachers.
Thousands of plant employees and subcontractors march to defend a plant accused of dumping lead. The next day, dozens of activists and toddlers march to denounce lead poisoning.

issuenote: Four gunmen open fire on a PRD politician.  Two of his companions are killed.
Farmers protest to demand government aid during a drought.
Teachers protest to demand salary hikes.
A popular TV show host linked to drug traffickers is gunned down in a brazen day-time attack on a highway.
Thousands of people march against a crime wave, which recently claimed the life of a popular television personality.
A demonstration was held against Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas.
Prisoners riot during a regular search of the prison's sleeping quarters.
Six gunmen attack the presidential guard as they draw their payroll from a bank.  The gunmen steal nearly $50,000 dollars after the brazen attack.

actor1: Program for Equal Participation of Women
issuenote: Housewives strike to draw attention to the fact that housework benefits society as a whole.  This forces some husbands to do housework for the first time in their lives.
Prisoners riot after the warden reduces family visitations from six to two hours.
A celebration of Mexico's first victory in a major international soccer tournament turns violent when fans begin throwing cans at police.
Four attackers exchange gunshots with the top anti-drug prosecutor.
A mob of EZLN supporters attacks an army patrol in Chiapas.  Several people are wounded.
14,000 union members protest government plans to increase private investment in the state owned electric power industry.
600 police protest for higher pay.  During the march, protesters recognize a police commander in civilian clothes and beat him up.
Unknown gunmen kill a local leader of a small political party, minutes after he voted.
Two people are wounded in election related violence.
Prisoners stage a small riot over a recent flood that inundated the prison.
Hundreds of people block a highway to protest sandbagging that they say compounded recent flooding.  Police beat and arrest many of the protesters.
Hundreds of prisoners take over a prison to protest flood inundation and food shortages.
Protesters attempt to march downtown to demonstrate against bank foreclosures and high interest rates.  They are beaten by police, and a congressman is injured.
El Barzon organizes protesters, who ride horses from Cuidad Juarez to Mexico City to protest against NAFTA's farm policies.

Masked gunmen, alleged to be Maya Indians from Chamula, attack a prison, leading to a mass prison break and riot.  The Indians are in conflict with local authorities over the right to practice Evangelical Protestantism.

Protesters demonstrate and clash with police at the US embassy in an event that coincides with Seattle WTO protests. Several hundred university students demand the release of protesters arrested at the WTO meeting.
Rebel sympathizers commemorate the Zapatista rebellion.
Hundreds of riot police march to demand salary increases and the dismissal of their commander.
Gunshots are fired from a mountain onto rebels returning home from a shopping trip.  Three rebels are killed.
About 100 student supporters of a recently ended student strike march through campus and clash with anti-strike students.

Students take over a school over claims that state officials are profiting from the proceeds of school lands, they are arrested. Angered by these arrests, activists surround dozens of police officers and hold them hostage.
Four armed assailants assassinate the Tijuana police chief.
Villagers march to demand the release from prison of 87 Indians they say are falsely accused of participating in the 1997 Acteal Massacre.

25,000 members of Antorcha, a radical peasant organization affiliated with the PRI, camp out in front of the governor's office to demand 200 plots of land they claim were promised to them in a recent election campaign.
Gunmen open fire at a hotel, killing a man identified as an ex-federal agent accused of having drug ties.
Unknown gunmen assassinate a former prison director a little more than a month after he resigned his post under accusations of mismanagement.
A former homicide chief linked to drug cartels is gunned down.
Four men are killed in a gangland-style killing.  The motive may have been drugs or a dispute over a romance.
Students occupy a dozen buildings on the UNAM campus to demand changes in university policies and administration. They also call for the release of detained student leaders arrested for a strike.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: A police commander investigating possible links between drug cartels and government officials is gunned down.
Thousands of people march to protest the deployment of security forces seeking to prevent students from seizing the UNAM university over the Easter break.

target1: Official in the Attorney General's office
issuenote: Gunmen open fire on a vehicle containing a top official in the Attorney General's office.
Gunmen assassinate a police homicide chief.
Gunmen break into a house and kill three people in a dispute between drug traffickers.
Opposition party farmers and police clash in a fight over a warehouse full of construction material.
20,000 teachers protest to demand salary increases and prompt payment of salaries.
3000 police officers march to protest the failure of the government to pay them a bonus and to demand an end to corruption.
UNAM student radicals, holdouts from the April 1999 strike, scuffle with faculty.
Gunmen kill two children and two adults in retaliation for the murder of a man a few days earlier.
The 1500 member airline stewards union, ASSA, strikes to demand a salary increase.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Gunmen ambush police as they search for a group of bandits.
More than 8000 people march in a gay pride parade and demand equal rights.
Prisoners riot after guards deny them a getaway car.
PAN supporters attack vote counting offices, burning 85000 ballots.
PAN supporters attack vote counting offices, burning 85000 ballots.
PRI supporters try to storm an electoral office, clashing with police.

Peasants storm the PRI headquarters after the party's electoral loss; they demand that the party pay more attention to grassroots organizations like theirs and that a jailed leader be freed from prison.
More than 100 employees of the transportation ministry strike to protest their transfers to other jobs.  Clashes erupt with police.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: About 50 farmers clash with private security guards outside the PRI headquarters to demand the release of a man arrested for squatting on public land.
Hundreds of women march to demand that men share domestic chores.
Unknown gunmen kill the Guerrero state comptroller on a rural highway.
A pro government paramilitary group evicts Zapatistas from a village at gunpoint.
Autoworkers strike to demand a wage increase.  After five days, the government declares the strike illegal and orders the strikers back to work.
Violence occurs between two PRI factions.  A PRI activist who lost a recent mayoral election urges her supporters to attack loyalists of Chimalhuacan's new mayor.
Auxiliary police storm their headquarters to demand the resignation of their commander.  They attack fellow officers, who are rescued by the arrival of riot police.
Hundreds of police march to protest the detention of four colleagues who shot and killed a thief during a gun battle.
Thousands march to commemorate the 32nd anniversary of the day a security battalion opened fire on student protesters.
Workers hold a rally to protest a recent recommendation by the national antitrust watchdog that the state owned airline Cintra be split up and privatized.
More than 4500 government workers protest the refusal of Mexico's president to hand out farewell bonuses at the end of his term.
Opponents of a candidate for president of the Confederation of Mexican Workers protest outside a union meeting and then force their way inside.
Residents of a village attack 200 federal police officers who were launching an offensive to arrest a group of paramilitaries charged with the 1997 Acteal Massacre.
Thousands of sugar workers strike over salaries and retirement benefits.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Riots erupt in the Tepito neighborhood after a police raid seizes seven trucks loaded with stolen merchandise. Angry shopkeepers and residents clash with police, and looters take over the streets that night.
Farmers block access to oil fields and a petrochemical plant to demand compensation for damaged coconut crops.
Auxiliary police upset at not receiving a bonus block streets in the capital and fire their guns, clash with regular police.
PRI and PRD legislators brawl in the Tabasco state legislature over the naming of an interim governor after an October gubernatorial election is annulled.
A group of eight men led by a top municipal official charge into the home of a journalist and open fire.
A group of Canadian and American peace activists stage a hunger strike in favor of the Zapatistas.
About 500 Indians take over a town hall to demand that the mayor step down. The conflict stems from a dispute between PRI and PRD supporters.
Thousands protest to demand the peaceful, legal resolution of an election dispute in Tabasco state.
Hundreds of PRI supporters hurl bottles and sticks to prevent court appointed election authorities from reaching their offices.
A man sends a bomb through the mail to his sister in-law, who was handling a divorce case.
Drug traffickers attack and rob seven members of a family.
Subway workers strike to force the government to give the union control over the naming of the subway's income chief.

1000 student supporters of the UNAM student strike protest on the one year anniversary of the police raid that ended that event. Protesters, including some members of the strike, detain 33 staff and faculty.
Youths riot in response to a police raid on illegal markets in the Tepito neighborhood.

Hooded gunmen attack a meeting at the home of a town councilor, demanding to know the location of a rancher. When the attendees say they do not know, the gunmen massacre them. The crime is believed to be connected to drug trafficking.
geo_comments: No Limoncito de Ayala found. Limoncito in Sinaloa used here.

issuenote: Members of an EZLN splinter group dash into a town on the edge of Mexico City, fire guns into the air and spray graffiti on buildings.

elocal: San Cristobal de las Casas; Oaxaca City; Cuautla; Mexico City
issuenote: The EZLN stages a protest and marches from San Cristobal to Mexico City to lobby for an Indian rights bill.  The march is led by Subcommandante Marcos himself.

elocal: San Cristobal; Oaxaca City; Cuautla; Mexico City
issuenote: The EZLN stages a protest and marches from San Cristobal to Mexico City to lobby for an Indian rights bill.  The march is led by Subcommandante Marcos himself.

elocal: San Cristobal; Oaxaca City; Cuautla; Mexico City
issuenote: The EZLN stages a protest and marches from San Cristobal to Mexico City to lobby for an Indian rights bill.  The march is led by Subcommandante Marcos himself.

elocal: San Cristobal; Oaxaca City; Cuautla; Mexico City
issuenote: The EZLN stages a protest and marches from San Cristobal to Mexico City to lobby for an Indian rights bill.  The march is led by Subcommandante Marcos himself.

Protesters gather outside a meeting of the World Economic Forum to demand that political and business leaders do more for the world's poor. The protests escalate to riots; demonstrators throw rocks and police charge through barricades.
1500 ranchers and small land owners march to protest land seizures by the Zapatistas.

Farmers and ranchers, backed by Lacandon Indians, protest to demand that Congress modify an Indian rights bill advocated as a peace measure with the Zapatistas. Protesters demand the return of land seized by rebels.

target1: San Bartolome de los Llanos Alliance
issuenote: Rival peasants groups clash in a land dispute.  Members of a group affiliated with the PRI are ambushed by a leftist group called The House of the People.
Teachers strike and protest nationwide for higher salaries.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Flight attendants at Mexico City's international airport strike for higher wages.
Mayors representing all three of the major political parties gather with thousands of residents to protest an Indian Rights bill, which they say is inadequate.
Fishermen from five unions seize a distribution center in response to a decision by the national oil company to stop selling diesel fuel at industrial prices.
Over 100 people protest outside the US Embassy, carrying coffins representing thousands of Mexicans who have died trying to cross in the US.
Indians groups protest against an Indian rights amendment to the constitution as it passes the state legislature.  Indians claim it will not bring the peace it is intended to bring.
Unknown gunmen fire shots outside the home of the central bank governor.
A group called F-26 protests outside the Italian embassy to demonstrate against the death of an Italian protester at the hands of police during a G-8 meeting in Genoa.
About two dozen people protest outside the US embassy to demonstrate against US Navy bombing of Vieques Island.
A mob kills a man accused of stealing a statue of Mary Magdalene.

Zapatista supporters seize six Secretary of Social Development officials and demand expanded federal benefits. 300 police officers then storm the town and liberate the hostages. Two days later, peasants protest against excessive use of force.
Zapatista sympathizers block a highway in Chiapas to protest the passage of a watered-down Indian rights bill.
A prison uprising occur.  Convicted murderers seize guards and then kill two of them before committing suicide.
An accused robber is killed by a vigilante mob of shopkeepers.

actor1: Revolutionary Armed Forces of the People
issuenote: A small leftist group plants explosives at five branch banks recently purchased by Citigroup. Several of the devices explode, but no one is killed. The leftist group is angered because the banks were bailed out by taxpayers.
Thousands of farmers protest government farming policies, which has depressed coffee, sugar, and grain prices.
200 Protestants take 3 state officials hostage to demand that they negotiate an end to an ongoing religious dispute with Catholics in a neighboring town.
Volkswagen workers strike to demand higher wages.
7 drug traffickers in the employ of Vidal Gomez, a major drug lord, are found executed over the course of a week.  Four others are found dead in El Paso, USA.
A few dozen protesters gather outside a meeting of WTO trade ministers.
Small bombs explode in front of a Chevrolet dealership and a McDonald's.
A prison revolt occurs.  Police storm the prison after inmates seize control.
notes: Location refers to city in the state of Sonora, near the US border, not the city of the same name near Veracruz.

issuenote: A prominent human rights lawyer is found dead, and a note left on her body warns that the same could happen to others.
Human rights organizations demonstrate outside government offices, protesting the possibility that federal prosecutors could take over the investigation into the killing of a human rights lawyer.
Two federal judges are gunned down.
A lawyer who defended a drug dealer turned informant is attacked.
Inmates at a youth prison riot against living conditions.
Juvenile inmates riot twice in two days to demand better food.
Machete wielding farmers organized by the PRD march through the city streets to protest the expropriation of their land for a new international airport.
40,000 teachers strike to demand that President Vicente Fox increase federal funding for education.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Hundreds of Mexican truckers block bridges into the United States for three days in protest of US refusals to allow some Mexican drivers into the country.
Residents erect sandbag barricades and dig trenches to prevent land expropriation and construction of an airport in the area.
A magazine editor is gunned down after publishing an article linking an ex-mayor with drug traffickers.
notes: There are several cities under this name.  This event occurs in Tamaulipas state.

issuenote: Residents of Teojomulco raid Santiago Xochiltepec in an ongoing land dispute, firing hundreds of shots at the village school.
Six people are executed.

actor1: Local police working for Ismael Zambada
issuenote: Local police working for Ismael Zambada killed Ramon Arellano Felix and another person.
Residents of Xochiltepec raid Las Huertas and kill one person as a result of an ongoing land dispute.
Armed men attacked the Excelsior newspaper.

actor1: National Mining, Metallurgical and Similar Workers Union
issuenote: Miners stage a six week strike against a copper mining concern with facilities across the nation.
notes: Start date is estimated.

issuenote: A prison riot occurs over the poor treatment of inmates at the hands of the guards.
Prisoners stage a hunger strike to demand their release.  They go so far as to sew their own mouths shut.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Clashes erupted between Indian members of PRI and PRD, and one was killed.

1000 teachers and parents pull children out of school to protest and deliver petitions to local officials decrying proposals to build a natural gas terminal in the town, which relies primarily upon Spring Break tourism.
notes: Date is estimated.

issuenote: 15 masked gunmen kill four members of a peasant family and then steal their mule and other possessions.
notes: San Juan is 40 miles north of Mazatlan.

issuenote: Snipers kill four family members traveling by car after leaving a family party.
geo_comments: Location is estimated as just south of Culiacan, Mexico

issuenote: Protesters demonstrate against a plan to expropriate land for an airport.  American activists join the protest and are expelled from the country by the government.
Armed suspects in suits drive up and kill the commander of the capital's anti-drug squad.  Police admit that the suspects are active-duty police.

Gunmen round up five ranchers, load them onto a pickup truck, drive them to a ravine, and shoot them one by one.  The attack is believed to be aimed at peasants that have carried drugs for the rival Ismael Zambada organization.
geo_comments: description indicates that the village is in Durango.

issuenote: The Arellano Felix cartel sends 23 men in ski masks into the town of La Ajoya and guns down 12 people at a Mother's Day party.  The attack is believed to be aimed at peasants that have carried drugs for the rival Ismael Zambada organization.

10 members of the EPR attack a contingent of government agents guarding a water treatment facility.  The attackers leave behind a note arguing that their attack was to challenge the authority of the police and state agents.
Hundreds of teaching students from 15 colleges demonstrate in Amalcingo.  A small group of students storm the Morelos state legislature and hold deputies hostage for 15 hours.
Hundreds of teaching students from 15 colleges demonstrate in Amalcingo.  A small group of students storm the Morelos state legislature and hold deputies hostage for 15 hours.
notes: Start date is estimated.  Amalcingo is near Cuernavaca.

issuenote: About 100,000 municipal workers, half of Mexico City's municipal work force, walk off their jobs to protest the firing of three workers and the loss of benefits, including allowances to buy work clothes.
Residents of rival communities clash.  Gunmen ambush a truckload of people on a mountain road, apparently as a result of a land dispute.
notes: Agua Fria is about 30 miles southwest of Oazaca City.

issuenote: Farmers seize six workers, including a Bulgarian engineer, in protests over land expropriation for an airport.
Gunmen kill 8 people in an attack.  The attack is believed to be aimed at peasants that have carried drugs for the rival Ismael Zambada organization.
notes: Date is estimated.

issuenote: 600 pig farmers block an international bridge on the US border to demand that the government offer them the same subsidies that US farmers receive.
Gunmen shoot and kill 5 people returning home from a political rally.

Farmers and their sympathizers protest the expropriation of land to build an international airport; clash with police in Santa Catarina.  After the riot is pacified, another group of farmers seize hostages in San Salvador Atenco.

Farmers and their sympathizers protest the expropriation of land to build an international airport; clash with police in Santa Catarina.  After the riot is pacified, another group of farmers seize hostages in San Salvador Atenco.
PAN and PRI supporters protest against one another over a disputed election in Juarez.  Masked gunmen attack the rallies, gunning down two men in a parking lot in broad daylight.
Fishermen in Salina Cruz block the entrance to a refinery to protest against environmental damage.
Subway workers stage a wildcat strike against unsafe working conditions.
15,000 Mayans protest against the government's infrastructure development plan.
A group of about 50 local Catholics with hunting rifles open fire on Protestant families as they take their children to school.
Zapatistas and PRI supporters clash over land ownership.
2000 Zapatista supporters wearing ski masks march through the streets, demanding that a government agent they claim killed a Zapatista leader be handed over to them.
Dozens of residents protest and block streets around the site of a former cultural center where Costco plans to build a store.  Riot police arrive and arrest many of the protesters.
Police making a routine traffic stop are gunned down when four men riding in the car they just stopped grab machine guns and spray their cruiser.
Gunmen affiliated with the PRI burst into a meeting of rebel officials and open fire, killing two.
Los Aguilares and Zapatista rebels clashed, killing one.
Police responding to a missing-persons report at an opium farm come under fire from suspected drug traffickers.
Police evict squatters living illegally in an ecological reserve, triggering a riot.
Thousands demonstrate on Columbus Day against racial discrimination.
The Collective Front of Anarchist Vegetarians demonstrated against McDonald's. Police make arrests.
Hundreds of fishermen protesting a new law that prohibits them from trawling for shrimp in a marine reserve form a human chain across a highway, leaving scores of American tourists stranded.

30 protesters led by a former union leader storm the office of a Mexican newspaper and scuffle with security guards.  The protest is designed to frighten away investors interested in buying the paper.
2000 members of the PRI protest against alleged electoral fraud in Gerrero state, alleging that two mayors of the leftist PRD assumed office by fraud.  The protesters seize government buildings.
2000 members of the PRI protest against alleged electoral fraud in Gerrero state, alleging that two mayors of the leftist PRD assumed office by fraud.  The protesters seize government buildings.
An angry mob beats to death two of three youths allegedly trying to rob a taxi driver.
Protesters storm the lower house of Congress on horseback, and occupy the legislative chamber for more than an hour. Teachers at the National Coordination of Education Workers demand higher wages.
More than 600 employees at a newspaper strike to protest a lack of benefits and the firing of several co-workers.
About 100 angry farmers block a US border bridge and dozens more demonstrate in Mexico City against the lifting of tariffs on agricultural products stipulated by NAFTA.
About 100 angry farmers block a US border bridge and dozens more demonstrate in Mexico City against the lifting of tariffs on agricultural products stipulated by NAFTA.
A former governor and dozens of other inmates at one of Mexico's toughest prisons refuses food to protest the reduction of visiting house.
Two men gun down a federal legislator and his brother.
Employees of rival TV stations have a fistfight outside a courthouse in a dispute over broadcast frequencies.
Two Catholics are killed in bout of religious violence.
geo_comments: I used the coordinates of Tres Cruces

issuenote: Gunmen ambush police, sparking a gun battle, at the site of a long-running religious dispute between Indian-style Catholic traditionalists and Evangelical Protestants.
geo_comments: I used the coordinates of Tres Cruces

issuenote: 25 groups organize tens of thousands of farmers to protest against NAFTA, demanding greater protection from US imports and more government aid.
Two dozen demonstrators protest against US corporation setting up operations in Mexico.
Hundreds of Mexican laborers protest at the US embassy to demand back wages for working on American farms and railroads 60 years prior.

Hundreds of doctors, nurses and other health care workers march to protest what they call unfair blame that has been cast upon them for a spike in infant mortality at a local hospital in December. They blame the government.
About 200 people form local political parties, small vendor cooperatives, and INGOs hold anti-war protests in front of the US Embassy.
Over 10,000 protesters demonstrate against US plans to attack Iraq.

About 20 Mexican and Spanish citizens hold demonstrations in front of the Spanish Embassy during a visit by Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar, decrying his support for American plans to attack Iraq.
A group of 300 farmers, anarchists, and students rip apart voting booths in municipal elections.
Drug traffickers shoot down two Mexican police helicopters in a sign of escalating violence.
Several thousand people demonstrate against a possible war in Iraq.
Anti-war protesters march in several cities.  Some anarchists are arrested after throwing rocks at the American embassy.
Anti-war protesters march in several cities.  Some anarchists are arrested after throwing rocks at the American embassy.
Daily anti-war protests occur.
About 500 radical student and activist groups hurl paint bombs at the Mexican stock exchange and the US embassy, protesting the war in Iraq.  Others join the protest to call for affordable housing.
Villagers who say they suffered from psychological and property damage from detonations unleashed by a Chinese petroleum exploration company hold 50 workers hostage to demand compensation.
Seven people are shot dead in drug related violence.
Less than 10,000 protesters march against the Iraq War.
An angry crowd stones to death an Indian man accused of practicing witchcraft.
Gunmen dressed as police kill six family members in a suspected drug gang dispute.
Hundreds of firefighters strike after contract negotiations break down.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Two men walk into a cafÈ and gun down a drug smuggler.
A prison riot occurs.
Protesters bar residents from voting in state elections, tearing apart voting booths and forcing election officials to throw out the few ballots that were cast.
Several thousand radical teachers belonging to dissident groups that oppose the official union leadership tear down police barricades in front of the president's residence, demanding higher wages.
Gunmen burst into a bar and kill four people in a suspected drug-related attack.
Gunmen kill a former police director as he is chatting with neighbors in his front yard.

elocal: Near the Guatemalan border in Chiapas state
ilocal: Near the Guatemalan border in Chiapas state
issuenote: A disagreement between two families turns into a machete and gun fight.
geo_comments: Centroid of Guatemala border of Chiapas State

issuenote: About 500 street vendors riot and clash with police over a plan to restrict their movement during an upcoming municipal festival.
Antigovernment protesters disrupt congressional midterm elections by smashing windows, blocking the installation of polling stations, and beating townspeople who turn out to vote.
Gunmen spray bullets into a van carrying a commander in the federal investigative police, killing him and his brother.

About 300 residents protest against the radical leaders of the July 11, 2002 hostage crisis, demanding they be allowed to hold elections and regain a formal police force and government, both of which had been forced out of town.
Gustavo Guerrero, a farmer, sets himself on fire to protest local authorities, who had prevented him from selling melons in the main square.
Dozens of residents of a mountainside community scuffle with police after walking out of talks aimed at ending a land dispute with residents of Santo Tomas Ajusco.
Unknown gunmen ambush a truck full of people.  The victims appear to be planting pine trees when they are shot.
Juvenile inmates riot at a detention facility.  30 inmates escape, police use tear gas during the riot.
Hundreds of demonstrators close down a bridge on the border to protest WTO talks in Cancun.
Several thousand students and political activists march to mark the 35th anniversary of the student massacre in 1968.

actor1: Revolutionary Confederation of Workers and Peasants
issuenote: A group closely related to the PRI organizes a protest against the government's plan to open the energy sector to private investment.
A Pentecostal pastor is shot dead in an apparent incident of religiously motivated violence.
Prison gangs riot after the theft of some prisoners personal property by other inmates.
Demonstrators march in Mexico City and dozens of cities around the world, calling on the Mexican government to respond to the killings of hundreds of women in Chihuahua state over the last decade.
80,000 union members, left wing activists, and farmers march to protest plans to raise taxes on food, medicine, and to sell state-owned assets.
A gang armed with automatic weapons attacks a ranch, killing 8 people.
Members of the Central American Salvatrucha gang attack a train full of illegal immigrants and rob them.
Two peasant groups clash in a dispute over farmland.
At least 25 army deserters overpower guards at a prison and engineer the escape of several convicted members of the Gulf Cartel.
Dozens of university students protest at the international airport, voicing opposition to the presence of US security agents.
Dissidents and leftist sympathizers clashed with police, and police killed one.
Wives and relatives of some of Mexico's criminals and suspects hold a protest to demand better prison conditions.

target1: Agents of the attorney general's office
issuenote: Two agents and an army captain are shot to death while driving an expensive foreign car without license plates.
Guzman is gunned down at La Palma prison.
Protesters charge a mayor with abuse of power, nepotism, and sexual harassment, forcing him to quit and flee the town.

elocal: Vicente Fox's ranch 185 miles northwest of Mexico City
ilocal: Vicente Fox's ranch 185 miles northwest of Mexico City
issuenote: Braceros demonstrated against the government.
Jane Fonda, Sally Field, and Christine Lahti lead a march, urging the government to provide sufficient resources to help investigate the killing of hundreds of women in the last decade.
Drug traffickers killed a policeman in an attack on a police helicoptor.
50,000 supporters of Mexico City mayor Obrador protest against government officials accusing him of corruption.
Gunmen ambush the governor of Oaxaca state, slightly wounding him.  Federal authorities later conclude that the incident was faked, although the governor disagrees.
Hundreds march in an anti-war protest to mark the one year anniversary of the war in Iraq.
1700 unionized workers strike to demand higher wages.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Radical students and their supporters burst into the offices of the university disciplinary board and steal student records in an effort to avoid expulsion.  After the attack, about 50 other people block traffic to demonstrate.

target1: Rival Indian groups aligned with the PRD
issuenote: Hundreds of Zapatistas protest the loss of water service after refusing to cooperate in maintaining and paying for the area's water system; the Zapatistas attend a protest against this but are then attacked by rival Indians as they leave.
A convoy of Zapatista sympathizers returning from a celebration comes under attack, leaving about a dozen people injured.
geo_comments: Estimated middle point of Southern Mexico

issuenote: A bomb explodes at a Red Snapper restaurant, just 200 meters from the US border.
notes: Town in Tamaulipas state.

issuenote: Tens of thousands of government employees march to criticize government proposals to streamline the Social Security Institute's pension and benefits system.
Hundreds of protesters march to show support for the Cuban government, one week after President Vicente Fox tells the Cuban ambassador to leave Mexico. They decry the government and condemn the US.
Protesters burn a police truck and two shacks used to house provisions for officials.
notes: Date is estimated.

issuenote: An angry crowd briefly takes a hostage and clashes with police as they try to quell a local land dispute.
Comando Jaramillista Morelense 23 de Mayo attacked banks.
Activists violently protest against an international economic summit, throwing rocks, sticks, signposts, and barricades.  Several international activists are arrested and deported.
30 upper-middle class protesters demonstrate against high crime rates.
Gangs clash in southern Mexico in a battle over the control of drug and human smuggling routes.

actor1: National Alliance in Defense of Dairy Farmers
issuenote: Dairy farmers, with cows in tow, protest in front of the US Embassy to call upon the Mexican government to subsidize the production of milk.
Gunmen ambush and kill the editor of a newspaper, widely known for reporting on the influence of drug traffickers.
Hundreds of thousands of Mexicans clad in white stage a silent march to protest against kidnapping, violent crime, and the failures of law enforcement.
Six Basques accused of belonging to the ETA stage a hunger strike to protest an order for their extradition to Spain.
Miners strike to demand a profit-sharing agreement and other benefits.
notes: Start date is estimated.

issuenote: Disgruntled city workers protest to demand the mayor's reinstatement.  The protests lead to the mayor's dismissal.
Thousands of union workers protest reforms to the country's social security system.
Some 3000 protesters march through downtown and past the US embassy to mark the 51st anniversary of the July 26 uprising in Cuba.
PRD and PRI supporters clash over a state election.  This is the first reported deadly incident of election violence in many years.
Violent protests occur as an ex-Mayor and his supporters demand that the mayor be reinstated.  Police use tear gas.
Rival groups of protesters clash over property claims.
Police attempting to evict 200 squatters from a plot of land are greeted with gunfire, sticks, and stones.

Angry union members surround the Senate building and fight bloody battles with police to protest a pension reform bill.  The protesters engage in running battles and blockades that cut off traffic on dozens of streets.

actor1: Committee to Defend the Teotihuacan Valley
issuenote: Protesters demonstrate against plans to build a Wal-Mart near ancient ruins.
Hundreds of enraged residents capture the mayor and three other municipal officials and throw them in jail for several days, accusing them of embezzling funds from public works projects.
Thousands of protesters protest against corruption accusations leveled against Mexico City's mayor.
Bursts of automatic gunfire result in the death of a man as he drives his pickup truck through a residential neighborhood.
More than 1000 squeegee men, beggars, street vendors, and prostitutes march to protest a new zero-tolerance law inspired by similar efforts in New York City.
Workers at the only plant that produces the New Beetle strike for higher wages.
Attackers with automatic weapons kill two men.
Mexico City's leftist mayor leads about 200,000 protesters in a march to protest efforts to impeach him and uses the event to unveil his 2006 presidential platform.
A shootout occurs between men in a pair of vehicles.

target1: Brother of the boss of the Sinaloa Cartel
issuenote: Gunmen shoot the brother of the boss of the Sinaloa drug cartel.
Unknown gunmen rob an armored car outside a Sam's Club.
Thousands of students, union leaders, and activists march to commemorate the anniversary of the 1968 student massacre.  Police clash with a group of anarchists before the protest begins.
PRD legislators storm the lower house of Congress and seize the speaker's podium to prevent discussion of proposed funding changes for local education.  This occurs three days in a row.
A drug lord is gunned down inside a federal prison.
Dozens of cowboy-hatted farmers protest outside Nestle offices, saying current trade policies hurt Mexican coffee growers.

actor1: National Mining, Metallurgical and Similar Workers Union
issuenote: Workers at Mexico's biggest copper mine strike, charging that Grupo Mexico hasn't paid them the equivalent of 5 percent of its equity in a deal that was promised 15 years prior.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: 300 Mexican environmentalists and farm activists protest outside a meeting of agricultural researchers to decry the importation of genetically modified corn.
Demonstrators protest outside the US embassy against the war in Iraq.

actor1: Civic Front for the Defense of the Teotihuacan Valley
issuenote: Demonstrators protest outside ancient ruins in an effort to prevent the opening of a nearby Wal-Mart.
Violence occurs between police and citizens attending a PRD election rally.
Local police lie in wait in order to ambush a group of men that had allegedly threatened them.  The police instead open fire on a group of revelers in a case of mistaken identity.  7 are killed.
400 farmers march in their underwear to demand that the mayor return a parcel of land they claim City Hall took from them.  They end their protest by stripping off al their clothes.
A vigilante mob angry about recent child abductions corners plain clothed federal agents taking photos of students at a school and burns them alive, mistaking them for kidnappers.
9 bodies are discovered south of Cancun, including those of 3 federal agents.  Police blame an ongoing turf war between drug gangs.
A mob of 10 to 15 people forms to lynch two accused rapists; police move in and rescue the accused.
400 prison inmates stage a brief hunger strike to demand a fairer distribution of telephone and visiting hours.

State police take four people into custody, including a local justice of the peace.  A group of residents claim the authorities did have  warrants and retaliate by hurling stones, trash, and the taking of hostages.  Police use tear gas.

Members of the SITRASE truckers union blockade the site of new airport construction with their big rigs.  The incident grows out of an ongoing dispute between two unions, SITRASE and the Mexican Confederation of Workers, over jobs at the site.

More than 750 police and army troops raid the nation's top security prison after officials receive repeated warnings that two of the western hemisphere's most notorious drug bosses had joined forces behind bars.
Mexicans who worked in the US during a World War II guest worker program, and their heirs, protest to demand restitution of pension funds.
Gunmen lie in wait for prison guards to exit a maximum security prison.  They ambush and kill six of them, in an apparent attack by the Gulf Cartel against the government.
Federal agents and soldiers raid a prison in Matamoros to break up drug gangs.  This is the second such raid in a month, occurring less than a week after the killing of six prison employees.

issuenote: Assailants shoot two men to death in what is believed to be an incident of drug related violence.

About 60 residents briefly take four police officers hostage, protesting the handling of a car wreck earlier in the week.
Gunmen attack and seriously wound a journalist.  The journalist dies several weeks later.
Thousands of PRD supporters led by Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador protest a Congressional vote stripping him of immunity from criminal prosecution.
Alleged drug traffickers assassinate the director of a newspaper.
Three gunmen shoot dead two people outside a restaurant.

To protest Congress' vote stripping Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador of his immunity from prosecution, PRD conduct several nationwide protests. Several stage hunger strikes outside the President's residence, while some attempt to invade his ranch.
Hundreds of thousands of PRD supporters march to protest the prosecution of Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador.
More than 100 residents of an isolated Indian town beat six people accused of witchcraft.

More than 1000 motorcyclists drive en masse to the Monument of the Revolution in a protest responding to the death of a television actor run over earlier in the month while riding a motorcycle.

Assailants gun down two couples, and five others.
A municipal police chief is gunned down as he leaves his house.
At least three people, including a federal police officer, are gunned down.
The director of a state prison is shot to death in an ambush outside his home.
Hundreds protest a controversial remodeling project that is blamed for weakening the roots of historic India Laurel trees.
More than 100 citizens march to protest the deaths of hundreds of women in the last decade, and the recent sexual abuse and slaying of a 7-year old girl.
Gunmen ambush and wound a police commander.
Two federal agents are gunned down.
Municipal police open fire on a convoy of federal agents.
The commander of a federal police detail credited with a number of drug busts is shot to death.
A mob of unionists blockades a newspaper in a labor dispute, trapping journalists and other employees inside for over a month.  In July, the unionists attack the building, forcing their way inside.

issuenote: Contract negotiations end in a strike.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Five assailants kidnap an Argentine soccer coach.
More than 1000 people protest in front of the US embassy on the anniversary of the Cuban revolution.
More than 10,000 sugarcane growers march to protest plans by the president to veto a sugarcane bill passed by the Congress.
Armed men attack a drug safe house with automatic weapons and a rocket launcher.
A US resident is accidentally shot by a Mexican police officer.

A man goes on a rampage and kills 10 people before being wounded by police and killed by an angry crowd.
Unknown gunmen assassinate two unknown victims.
The director of investigative police for the state attorney general's office is gunned down as he leaves a restaurant.

issuenote: 2000 steelworkers strike to demand that alleged violations of their contract be settled and that seven fired workers be rehired.

Unknown gunmen killed a US soldier.

Two men are executed by unknown assailants.
Unknown attackers kill a state police officer; throw a grenade into a state police office.
A group of three drug-gang hitmen storm into a restaurant and execute the director of public safety and a bodyguard.

A federal anti-drug prosecutor is shot dead.
A civilian is shot dead by a lone gunman as he washes his car.
At least 300 residents of two communities affected by a 2004 oil spill prevent employees of Pemex from heading to work.
4 people are shot dead in drug related shootings.
4 people are shot dead in two separate incidents.
4 people are shot dead in two separate incidents.
Two men are shot dead in the city streets.
Prisoners riot after an inmate dies of a heart attack.  Police deploy to the prison and break up the riots.
A Roman Catholic priest is found hand cuffed and shot to death in what police say is an organized-crime killing.

issuenote: Transvestites, transsexuals, and male prostitutes protested against a serial killer who has killed a number of older women.
Greenpeace floats a hot-air balloon over Mexico City in a anti-genetically modified food campaign.
Parties unknown plant two bombs at branches of a Spanish-owned bank.  The first explodes, injuring no one.  The second bomb fails to detonate.

notes: The government accuses the killers of being members of the Zapatistas.  The Zapatistas deny those allegations.

issuenote: Prison gangs riot.
Two unknown assailants open fire on a group of youths.
Police officers proceed down a highway, searching for a group of suspected robbers and traffickers.  They are ambushed by the suspects, resulting a gun and machete fight.
Miners strike for better working conditions and to show support for a union leader accused of responding poorly to a mining tragedy.
Cubans riot at a prison to demand that they not be deported back to Cuba.
More than 20,000 union workers march to accuse the government of meddling in union affairs by seeking to oust its leader.
Heavily armed assailants ambush police officers.  Suspicion immediately falls on powerful drug gangs.
Gunmen attack an unmarked police truck.
Thousands of Indians and Farmers protest outside a meeting of the World Water Forum.  Groups of demonstrators battle with police, smashing patrol cars and hurling rocks.

Steel workers strike to protest the firing of their national union leader.  The strike escalates to a riot on April 20 when authorities unsuccessfully try to remove workers from an occupied plant, leaving two dead.  The strike ends in August.
Hundreds of machete wielding farmers stage a two day blockade of a pumping plant to protest government plans for a dam on a waterway.
Two civilians are killed by an unknown number of gunmen.
Unidentified assailants throw a grenade at a home.
Two people die in a grenade attack on a restaurant, including the mayor's chauffeur.
Residents of a town riot after a policeman shoots and kills and local man, evidently mistaking him for a Central American during a raid on undocumented migrants.
Assailants armed with guns and grenades ambush a convoy carrying a top security official.
Unionists demonstrated against the US and American companies.

Street vendors rebel in response to efforts to relocate them.  They attack police, detaining hostages and taking control of the town.  Hundreds of law enforcement officials fire tear gas and crash through human barricades to retake the town.
More than 100 people blockade a highway to protest police brutality at a recent riot.
In a drug related shooting, a mechanic is gunned down outside his garage.
Unknown gunmen with assault rifles shoot and kill two men in a vehicle.

Teachers strike, demanding pay increases from the state government.  They clash with police in a series of violent riots.  Other protesters, including a mix of unionists and leftists, accuse the governor of rigging state elections.
notes: End date is estimated

issuenote: Assailants firing assault rifles kill a Nuevo Laredo police officer.  Police track the gunmen to a hideout, where one suspect is killed.
Gunmen shoot at a car carrying the family of a jailed businessman, hours before his wife was to release videos damaging to a presidential candidate.
Dozens of cyclists ride nude through Mexico City, demanding respect from motorists and protesting against the city's car-oriented culture.
Protesters march in silence, praying for peace and unity during the presidential elections.
Thousands of people, led by the leader of the Zapatistas, take to the streets to claim that the elections that are underway do not offer a real solution to the country's problems.
Thousands of Lopez Obrador supporters gather to protest announcements declaring Felipe Calderon the winner of the recent election.
More than 200,000 supporters of leftist presidential candidate Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador protest his defeat in the election.

Lopez Obrador supporters gather outside each of Mexico's 300 electoral districts and begin marches on the capital in order to demand a ballot-by-ballot recount after the recent election.  The protesters gather in the capital.
About 2000 people march against the rising tide of violence in the city.
A group of leftists waits for conservative candidate Felipe Calderon outside a meeting with trade unions, screaming insults at him and slamming their fists against his car as he leaves.
Dozens of people from the Lebanese immigrant community march to the Lebanese embassy to protest against the Israeli-Lebanon war.
Gunmen raid a pharmaceutical lab, killing four security guards and stealing about a ton of ephedrine.
Supporters of a leftist presidential candidate blockade the stock exchange and then march to the president's residence.
Two people are gunned down in their homes by assailants with automatic weapons.

500,000 supporters of leftist presidential candidate Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador march to demand a vote-by-vote recount of the recent election.  Protesters camp in the central square for weeks.  Some protesters stage violent riots.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Gunmen attack a newspaper critical of the Oaxaca state government.
Gunmen open fire on the continuing protests in Oaxaca.  Protesters seize the gunmen and hold them hostage.  They are later released to police custody.
Gunmen kill three people traveling to the protests in Oaxaca City.
Police searching for a protest leader are taken hostage by angry townspeople.
Autoworkers strike to demand a wage increase.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Gunmen attack a radio station taken over by striking teachers.

Assailants throw grenades at the offices of two newspapers.
Thousands of Obrador's supports protest and attempt to blockage the Congress in order to prevent the president from delivering an address.  They demand a vote recount for their candidate.
Two grenades are thrown at the door of a newspaper office.

Gunmen barge into a bar and toss five human heads onto the dance floor after ordering customers to get down on the floor.  The gunmen are believed to be linked to organized crime making a show of intimidation.
More than 100 teachers march in protest a visit by Felipe Calderon, recently declared as victor in the presidential election.
A police chief is killed in an organized crime hit.
Lopez Obrador supporters protested against the government after the courts ruled that Felipe Calderon was the winner of the election.
About 30 Lopez Obrador supporters throw eggs at Felipe Calderon's car in Torreon.

About 80 supporters of Lopez Obrador block cash registers and throw around merchandise at several Wal-Mart stores, demanding that the corporation stay out of Mexican politics and also alleging that it exploits workers.
A group of about 15 men open fire on an armored car as its guards drop off money at a currency exchange office.
Unknown gunmen murder four police passing by in an automobile outside a prison.
A criminal judge is stabbed 18 times by three persons.
A police commander is killed in a shootout with a criminal gang.
More than 5000 demonstrators march through Mexico City to commemorate the 1968 massacre of protesters.
The Michoacan drug cartel attacked a car dealership and two were killed.

Protesters march from Oaxaca and arrive in Mexico City to demonstrate against the governor of Oaxaca, whom they accuse of rigging elections and using force against them.

After a night of heavy drinking soldiers encountered a roadblock manned by demonstrators participating in ongoing protests in the city.  After the demonstrators refuse to let them pass, at least one of the drunks kills one person.
notes: The soldiers are off-duty, and this is not a government sanctioned attack; hence, it is not coded as repression.

issuenote: Assailants in cars shoot at the houses of PRI mayoral candidates.
Assailants in cars shoot at the houses of PRI mayoral candidates.
Supporters of rival parties clash, leading to 10 arrests.

A group of several dozen demonstrators interrupts a cathedral Mass, chanting against the governor of Oaxaca, whom they accuse of repressing protesters in that state.

target1: Federal Electoral Tribunal and headquarters of PRI

Six police officers are shot to death in an apparent ambush by drug smugglers.
Assailants shoot dead a US citizen.
Demonstrators storm a Wal-Mart, accusing the retailer of selling low-cost goods at the expense of workers, farmers, and public markets.

The ex-director of one of Mexico's oldest newspapers is found stabbed to death, a week after going public with his book criticizing the federal government, the business community, and newspaper employees.
A lone gunman follows a police chief and a city councilman into a convenience store and shoots them.

Singer Valentin Elizalde is assassinated after he closes a show with a song containing a video montage of people killed in drug related violence.
Lawmakers brawl on the floor of Congress after opposition legislators threaten to block the inauguration of Felipe Calderon.
About 1000 prisoners riot at a state penitentiary.  Around 150 manage to escape.

The PRD organizes a protest against the governor of Oaxaca, accusing him of rigging the 2004 election and demanding the withdrawal of federal police.

Assassins dressed as soldiers barge into two state police stations, assassinated five officers and two witnesses.  Many of the slain officers have ties to drug gangs.

About 500 residents of Acapulco march to demand an end to violent crime.
Thousands of coal miners stage a one-day strike on the anniversary of a mine-blast that killed 65 people.  The miners demand better working conditions.

Abortion opponents summoned by Mexico's Catholic Church march through the capital to protest bills that would legalize abortion in the first three months of pregnancy.

Supporters and opponents of a bill chant outside the Mexico City legislature as it passes a bill legalizing abortion.
Labor unions march to demand the release of protest leaders jailed during last year's anti-government riots.  Leftist sympathizers seize government offices.

Thousands of people take to the streets to demand the governor's resignation and briefly take two men hostage.
Masked members of the EPR shoot up the construction site of a jail.  Spray painted demands are left behind, demanding the release of political prisoners.

Workers at Mexico's largest copper mine strike to demand better safety conditions.  Police and miners clash in January after the strike is declared illegal.

Two federal agents who had participated in a drug-raid against a Chinese-Mexican businessman are gunned down.
A teacher's union demonstrates against proposed changes to the government pension system, briefly closing down the international border.
