Unknown gunmen mistakenly kill three newspaper vendors in an effort to assassinate journalists who had reported on reported on the discovery of a mass grave.

PRI supporters demonstrate and pull down a statue a Vicente Fox, which was erected just hours before.
Dozens of leftist protesters seize control of a Cathedral to demand that the government increase security in Mexico City.
Gunmen ambush a police convoy carrying suspected kidnappers to prison. Several people are killed in the ensuing gunfight, and two kidnappers are freed.
Farm activists stage a 36 hour blockade of the international border to protest unrestricted corn imports from the US, as established under the terms of NAFTA.
A gunfight erupts after police attempt to stop a van loaded with Gulf Cartel members.

Two federal agents are intercepted and gunned down.  A civilian is caught in the crossfire.
A shootout occurs between organized crime gunmen and police after authorities are called in because suspicious persons are seen following a man near the tourist zone.

Soldiers open fire on a truck that fails to stop at a checkpoint, resulting in the death of a teenager.

Gunmen capture, torture, and execute a police commander.

Gunmen storm a law office, shooting or strangling victims inside.  The event appears to be an act of score-settling between drug cartels.
Gunmen kill a musician at a concert in the latest in a series of assassinations of musicians.  The motives in these assassinations are unclear.

Three Mexican farming activists are found dead among a group of eight people who went missing.
Two masked gunmen attack a gym.
Thousands of Mexican cyclists ride naked through the streets to protest aggressive drives and carbon emissions from cars.
Teachers protest educational reform  A tanker truck carrying tar accidentally crashes into a highway toll booth seized by the protesters, killing seven people.
notes: All deaths in this event are accidental.
geo_comments: Location is the highway just west of Morelia

issuenote: A candidate for city council is assassinated.
Police officers patrolling in a town are kidnapped and killed.
The leader of the Sinaloa branch of the PRD is assassinated.

target1: Son of a PRI campaign coordinator
issuenote: The son of a PRI campaign coordinator is handcuffed and shot dead.
Assailants fire upon a van carrying a local legislative candidate and her family.
Gunmen assassinate a mayoral candidate.
Gunmen attack the house of a PAN candidate for mayor.
17 people are kidnapped from their homes.
Gunmen kill eight people in an attack.
Gunmen are traveling in pickup trucks when they run into patrolling soldiers, trigging a gunfight.
A crime reporter is shot dead along with another unidentified victim.

elocal: El Terrero; El Cubo; El Ramanse
issuenote: Gunfights erupt in a group of three villages, driving over 1000 refugees into another nearby town.

elocal: El Terrero; El Cubo; El Ramanse
issuenote: Gunfights erupt in a group of three villages, driving over 1000 refugees into another nearby town.

elocal: El Terrero; El Cubo; El Ramanse
issuenote: Gunfights erupt in a group of three villages, driving over 1000 refugees into another nearby town.
Five people are executed and their bodies are found inside an abandoned pickup truck that was set on fire.
Five police officers are shot dead.
Gunmen open fire on a group of community vigilantes.
Gunmen block roads throughout Michoacan state and ambush police patrols.  Gunfights occur, resulting in two dead federal police officers and 20 dead gunmen.
Gunmen ambush and kill a high ranking navy official and the officer escorting him.
Gunmen burst into a home, killing six people.  The victims had earlier fled from threats from organized crime.
Nine bodies are found bound together and shot on an abandoned property.
notes: Dates are estimated.

issuenote: Teachers march on Congress as it debates educational reforms.  The teachers attempt to force their way into the legislative chamber, triggering a riot and a clash with police.  Thousands then gather and blockade the Congress.
Vigilantes attack local police, beating them with rifle butts, then briefly kidnap some municipal officials.
Eight prisoners are stabbed to death in a prison riot.
A leftist presidential candidate leads protests against the president's plan for tax reforms.
Four men hack to death a state legislator and wound a journalist.
A PRD state assembly member is shot dead.
Gunmen who are part of the armed wing of the Juarez cartel open fire on a crowd celebrating in a house after an amateur baseball game.
Police find three human heads along with a note.
notes: Date is estimated.

issuenote: Gunmen on motorcycles open fire on a bar.
Gunmen shoot three people outside a convenience store.
Attackers shoot a group standing outside a bar.
Hundreds of teachers protest education reform and block the main road to the international airport.  Some clash with police.
Thousands of teachers and students protest against education reform and to honor victims of a 1968 massacre of protesters.  A small group of self-described anarchists clashes with riot police.
A clash occurs between local police and members of the New Generation Cartel.
A police chief is shot dead by unknown assailants on a roadway.
Soldiers kill four gunmen who attacked them.
Marines kill three gunmen who attacked them.
A gunman disguised as a clown guns down a convicted drug lord.
Prison inmates rioted, and 7 were killed.

A self defense militia stages a march in the central stronghold of the Knights Templar cartel, protesting against the cartel.  The cartel attacks the militia, triggering a gunfight.  In retaliation the cartel attacks electrical facilities.
Several men are shot to death and left in a vehicle outside a bar.
Gunmen attack troops.  13 civilians are killed in the crossfire.
A mob angry over the murder of a shopkeeper set fire to a town hall, the mayor's residence and police cars.
notes: Guadalupe Victoria is in Puebla state; not to be confused with similarly named towns in Durango or Baja California.

issuenote: Gunmen kill a sports journalist.
A prison riot occurs.
Vigilantes belonging to a self-defense movement take over a town, resulting in a clash that leaves two people dead.
Mexican police find a family of eight stabbed to death.  It is eventually learned that the murders were over a $115 debt that the father couldn't repay.
An armed group ambushes a federal police convoy.
Army soldiers kill four municipal workers by mistake as they return from a shooting range, mistaking them for criminals.
200 people gather to protest at the town hall over the shooting death of four municipal workers by army soldiers.
Parties unknown kill 11 people and then burn their bodies in an SUV.
Security forces confront a group of gunmen, trigging a clash.
The La Familia drug cartel kill one person.
The New Generation Cartel kill 5 people.
Nine people are shot dead in several attacks throughout the city.

target1: Deputy secretary-general of the National Revolutionary Movement (MNR)
issuenote: Unknown gunmen kidnap and kill an attorney and one of the leaders of a Salvadoran rebel group.
notes: Most likely the act of Rightist death squads.

issuenote: A Swedish embassy guard is killed in a politically motivated attack.  Sweden has recently been pressing Guatemala at the UN on its human rights record.
notes: Most likely the act of Rightist death squads.

issuenote: Security forces kill an American tour guide.
An anthropologist (Myrna Mack) is assassinated after issuing a report critical of the government's human rights record.
notes: Criminal investigations 10 years later implicate military officers in ordering and carrying out the attack.

issuenote: Two political activists are assassinated during the election campaign.
notes: Date is estimated.

issuenote: A federal deputy is assassinated.
notes: Date is estimated.

issuenote: Two candidates for the Central American parliament are assassinated.
The mayor of Jalapa is assassinated a week ahead of elections.
Soldiers fire indiscriminately, killing villagers.  This atrocity leads several foreign powers, including the US, to cut off aid.
Gunmen kill four peasants.  Witnesses identify the gunmen as soldiers.
A French couple that owned a fashionable restaurant are murdered.  The mutilation of their bodies suggests they were kill by paramilitaries for political purposes.
A bomb damages a government building.
notes: Date is estimated.

issuenote: Police shoot and kill one at a student protest.
Two bombs explode, injuring 14 people.
Students throw rocks at police to demand the release of 40 colleagues arrested at a protest.
A bomb explodes in front of the presidential palace.
notes: The fourth bombing attack in four weeks.

issuenote: A bomb explodes at a McDonalds restaurant.
notes: The fifth bombing attack in four weeks.

issuenote: A vigilante death squad shoots dead 10 people accused of raping and robbing local women.

Students violently demonstrate against a decision to issue student identity cards in order to exempt them from public transport fees.  The students claim the cards are really to make it easier for the government to track student leaders.
Rioting and demonstrations occur, with dissidents decrying the repression of student protests, rising electricity rates, and demanding an end to austerity measures.
notes: This event and related crises later prompt the president to stage a self-coup, disbanding Congress and the Supreme Court.

issuenote: Eight gunmen ambush a legislator's car, killing his bodyguard.  The attack is in apparent retaliation against the politician, who recently revealed the name of a police officer responsible for a student's death at a protest.
notes: This event and related crises later prompt the president to stage a self-coup, disbanding Congress and the Supreme Court.

issuenote: Public employees strike over increasing transportation and electricity prices.
notes: This event and related crises later prompt the president to stage a self-coup, disbanding Congress and the Supreme Court.

issuenote: The military forces the president out of office.
Protesters demonstrate against Vice President Espina, who has been declared president by the military after Jorge Serrano was deposed.
Jorge Carpio Nicole, cousin of the president and two-time presidential candidate, is assassinated with three body guards.
notes: The police arrest 10 members of the Guatemalan National Revolutionary Unity.  So, this is a possible civil war event.
geo_comments: About 75 miles northwest of Guatemala City.

issuenote: A journalist is assassinated.  Rightist death squads are suspected.
Gunmen open fire, and also destroy six electrical towers on the eve of a referendum on a new constitution.
Government workers strike for higher wages.
notes: Date is estimated.

issuenote: Rural organizations rally Indians at the national palace to demand benefits.

An American backpacking tourist in Santa Lucia Cotzualguapa is the target of rumors that she is a baby-snatcher.  Villagers try to lynch her, forcing police to take her into protective custody.  The mob riots, burning down government offices.
notes: Date is estimated.

issuenote: An American environmental activist is beaten into a coma in San Cristobal Verapaz  over rumors of baby-snatching, even after fleeing into the home of a justice of the peace.
The president of the constitutional court, Epaminondas Gonzalez Dubon, is assassinated.
A crowd on a bus threatens to lynch an American woman with an adopted girl, accusing her of kidnapping the girl.  Police take her to safety.
Parties unknown toss a bomb into the home of a brother of a peace negotiator.
A bomb is exploded at the home of a wealthy family.
Public doctors strike for higher wages.
notes: Dates are estimated.

issuenote: A lone kidnapper abducts two Mormon missionaries for 7.5 hours.  The kidnapper is arrested.
An American lawyer, the wife of a slain rebel leader, stages a hunger strike at the national palace to demand information on her husband.
Public transit workers strike.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Thousands riot over fare hikes in public transport.
Thousands riot over fare hikes in public transport.
About 1000 students demonstrate at funeral for a student killed by police in the prior week's protests.
Villagers riot against the local mayor, blaming inadequate water treatment for helping to spread cholera.
The American lawyer and wife of a guerrilla, slain by deaths squads with CIA collusion, stages a sit down protest with student activists outside a military base.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Soldiers attack a meeting of former refugees celebrating the one year anniversary of their return to Guatemala.  This event triggers a nationwide scandal and the resignation of the defense minister.
geo_comments: Location is a municipality within Chisec, Alta Verapaz

issuenote: Electrical workers strike to renegotiate their contracts.
notes: Dates are estimated.

issuenote: Gunmen spray the UN building with gunfire on the eve of the election.
Gunmen kidnap, torture, and murder a UN aid worker.
Gunmen abduct and kill a UN aid worker.
A local cattle rancher tries to kidnap an American aid worker.
5000 workers demonstrate against the president's economic policies.
A man tries to run over the president with his truck while he and his wife ride horses on a rural road.  The president's bodyguards shoot and kill the man.
Indians hold a rally/prayer meeting to exhort civil war combatants to make peace on the eve of a visit by the Pope.
Parties unknown kidnap an American woman.
notes: One of at least 150 people kidnapped since the beginning of the year.

issuenote: 300 unionists take over the Congress building to protest a law that would make it illegal for private sector employees to strike.
Three artists and a clergyman are mistaken for highway robbers by an angry mob.  They are lynched, and then burned alive.
A small protest occurs.  The demonstrators decry the amnesty given to rebels as a result of the war settlement.

Military police mutiny for an improved compensation package for post-war demobilization.  They claim that the rebels got a better deal and then refuse to leave their barracks, exchanging gunfire with government troops.

elocal: Granja Penal Pavon de Fraijanes prison; Granja Penal Provoncito de Guatemala prison
ilocal: Granja Penal Pavon de Fraijanes prison
issuenote: Prisoners riot and take control of a prison.  They demand improved sanitary and living conditions, and an investigation into corruption at the prison.
notes: Granja Penal Pavon de Fraijanes is 22 kilometers north of Guatemala City.  Granja Penal Provoncito de Guatemala is 23 km north of Guatemala City.  End date is estimated.

elocal: Granja Penal Pavon de Fraijanes prison; Granja Penal Provoncito de Guatemala prison
ilocal: Granja Penal Provoncito de Guatemala prison
issuenote: Prisoners riot and take control of a prison.  They demand improved sanitary and living conditions, and an investigation into corruption at the prison.
notes: Granja Penal Pavon de Fraijanes is 22 kilometers north of Guatemala City.  Granja Penal Provoncito de Guatemala is 23 km north of Guatemala City.  End date is estimated.

issuenote: 15,000 protesters march to protest the president's economic policies.
3000 inebriated youths attack police at a Def Leppard concert, triggering riots.
Gunmen slip into a fishing village by boat and then open fire, killing a family of four.
About 70 inmates riot at the country's main prison (Granja Penal Pavon), taking hostages.
Bandits attack a bus full of American students from St. Mary's College and commit several rapes.
Fans of rival soccer teams riot.
A bishop about to issue a scathing report on human rights during the civil war is beaten to death with a cement block.
notes: Suspicion immediately falls on right wing death squads.

issuenote: Black clad marchers demand justice for the killing of a Catholic bishop.
Kidnappers abduct American evangelical aid workers.  A fire fight with police occurs, and several hostages are rescued.
Farmers block roads to demand additional funding for land purchases.
A lynch mob holds a summary trial of accused robbers.  They then stone the accused to death and toss their bodies in a river.
A criminal gang robs a bus full of tourists.
Up to 100,000 people march to memorialize the murdered bishop Juan Gerardi and to demand justice from the government.
Unknown attackers murder the leader of a political party in advance of a referendum on constitutional reform.
Gunmen shoot and kill two supporters of the leading candidate in the country's presidential election.
A grenade attack occurs.
Violent protests occur.  Students protest against high bus fares.  Police use tear gas and water cannons, and a private security guard shoots a press photographer.  3 others die during the unrest.
notes: Start date is estimated.

issuenote: A mob stones to death a Japanese tourist and his tour's bus driver, believing the group had come to the village to steal children.  The mob then burns the bodies.
Four bodies of alleged gang members turn up, supposedly tortured to death by death squads.
Prisoners riot and attempt to escape.  They take hostages.  Negotiations end the riot, and no police force is used.

Police storm a prison in a pre-dawn drug raid, touching off a riot.  Authorities admit to having lost control of the prison some time ago.  It has instead come under the control of a gang called the Order and Discipline Committee.
notes: 18 miles southeast of Guatemala City

issuenote: Gunmen slaughter a family of Indian farmers in a land dispute.
A crowd of 200 villagers burn to death 8 men accused of running drugs and guns.
Masked gunmen wielding assault rifles shoot and kill an Indian activist and his secretary.
Villagers take two police chiefs hostage after their pickup truck runs over a woman.
Villagers take hostage 3 men accused of stealing a car.
A mob of 200 angry villagers pulls three suspected rapists from a police convoy and stones them to death while the police officers flee for their lives.

Protesters gather around the country to demand government help for poverty stricken farmers and to demand rights for indigenous peoples.  Unidentified gunmen open fire on one gathering, killing a protester.  Protesters riot.
A mob of villagers burn two men accused of stealing cattle.  One of the victims dies.
An angry mob stages a popular trial and then kills two brothers suspected in a stabbing.
Hundreds of villagers corner men accused of killing a local man.  They douse them with gasoline and then burn them.
As many as 1500 villagers stone to death two accused robbers.
Crowds beat to death a man accused of stealing chickens.
geo_comments: Location is about 150 miles north of the capital

issuenote: An accused chicken thief is tied to post and stoned, but police are able to rescue him.
Police save accused robbers from a mob of 400 villagers.  The police are themselves taken hostage by the mob.
geo_comments: About 140 km north of Guatemala City

issuenote: Gunmen open fire on a retired general who helped negotiate the end of the civil war.  In a separate attack, his daughter is also targeted.  One civilian dies in the crossfire.
More than 1000 people attack a judge after he issued an unpopular ruling in a rape case, hacking him to death with machetes and setting his body on fire.  They then hold 3 policemen hostage.
Students take over two schools to protest a program that requires high school students to teach at least one person to read in order to graduate.
Rival prison gangs battle one another in a bloody riot.
An angry mob beats to death an accused robber and murderer.
An angry mob burns to death a suspected robber.

About 180 students and Indian activists briefly take over the Spanish embassy, demanding to meet with officials from the president's office and demanding a say in who is named as head of the Indian development office.
An American nun who dedicated her life to helping civil war victims is gunned down.  While some claim it is an apparent robbery, the police suspect political motives.
Fishermen riot to demand access to an estuary on Martima company property.  They clash with police, and one of the fishermen is killed.
Gunmen attack the police for reasons unknown.
Unknown parties attempt to kidnap an American human rights investigator.
Prisoners riot and attempt to escape.   65 prisoners escape, and the president declares a state of emergency, allowing security forces to make arrests without warrants.
Former paramilitaries invade a village in a land dispute, burning dozens of homes, raping women, and kidnapping children.
Gunmen open fire on vehicles on a remote road as part of an ongoing land dispute.
Gunmen attack an ambulance carrying survivors of a massacre in Petan department.
An American hotel owner is gunned down.  Police rule out robbery as a motive.
A mob burns to death 8 people accused in a series of highway robberies.
geo_comments: Secoyala is about 250 miles north of the capital.

issuenote: Protesters demonstrate against a proposal to increase sales taxes and to add taxes on some businesses, with protesters accuse the US of pressuring Guatemala to approve the taxes. Protests escalate to riots and clashes and police repress.
notes: Dates are estimated.

issuenote: Nine students begin a hunger strike at the supreme court to protest a tax increase.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Unknown gunmen open fire on police.
Unknown gunmen kill three gang members.
Local Indians riot when police fail to make an immediate arrest in the case of a local man's murder on the region's main highway.  The mob burns down the local police station.
A mob kills three men accused of robbing supplies from a store.
geo_comments: Located somewhere in Baja Verapaz province.  Location estimated.

issuenote: A mob murders two suspected robbers.

target2: Supporters of the Guatemalan Republican Front
issuenote: Anti-government protesters clash with police and ruling party supporters outside of Congress as the president delivers his annual state of the nation speech.
53 air traffic controllers strike for higher wages.
Hundreds demand punishment for those responsible for massacres during the civil war.
Vendors destroy barricades they say make business difficult, clash with police.
Protesters call for the resignation of the president and vice-president.

target1: Regional director of the Patriot's Party
issuenote: The director of one of the Patriot Party's rural districts is gunned down, three days after having been the featured speaker at a protest.
Hundreds of peasants throughout northern Guatemala seize 14 coffee plantations to protest the unfair distribution of land.
Hundreds of villagers burn one man accused of witchcraft and hold hostage municipal officials accused of the same.
Gangs battle on the city streets.
An angry mob wielding machetes kills two men for stealing a soccer ball in the middle of a game.
A mob of peasants seizes control of the town of Tecpan and burns down the local police station in protest of a new federal tax scheme.
Ex-paramilitaries block roads, demanding payment from the government for their services during the civil war.
Unionists and students protest against a plan to pay-off civil war paramilitaries.
Doctors strike at public hospitals for better wages and more resources.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: An enraged mob beats to death an accused robber.
Peasants hold marches and blockade roads throughout central Guatemala to demand land.
A mob burns alive two men accused of murder.
Two gunmen board a bus, proceed directly to a government prosecutor, and then assassinate him.
Ex-paramilitaries block roads, demanding payment from the government for their services during the civil war.  Police break up the road blocks with tear gas.
A mob beats and lynches three men accused of robbery and murder.
Indigenous peoples protest against Columbus Day.
Gunmen open fire on the car of a Supreme Court justice.
Artists organize street protests to demand government action over the recent crime wave, which recently claimed the life of the member of a popular band.
Peasants occupy farmland, claiming it is being sold to outside parties.  In November, police forces evict the peasants in a violent battle.
notes: Start date is estimated.

issuenote: Gunmen attack the vehicle of a local mayor, who also happens to be the local director of the leftist political party and also of an indigenous organization.
A Christian Democrat legislator is killed under mysterious circumstances.

A small prison uprising occurs, and when negotiations between inmates and authorities fail, inmates decapitate a prisoner said to control the distribution of drugs and weapons.  The prison then factionalizes, and 18 die.
A mob kills a man in an incident of vigilante violence.
The former leader of Congress is shot dead while driving on property he owns.
A judge is assassinated outside a Catholic church.
A mob kills two men after the two try to murder another man.
Teachers strike for higher wages.  They stage frequent marches and occupations, even seizing an oil pumping station.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: A prison uprising occurs.
Former paramilitaries protest to demand compensation for their participation in the war; they stage marches and seize control of an oil pumping station owned by French oil company Perenco.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Former paramilitaries protest to demand compensation for their participation in the war; they stage marches and seize control of an oil pumping station owned by French oil company Perenco.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: A mob burns to death 4 suspected robbers.
Police raid a prison in order to reestablish full control following the Christmas Eve uprising.
Former paramilitaries demand compensation.  They march on Chicacao, burning down the municipal offices and taking hostage the provincial governor in San Francisco Zapotitlan.
Former paramilitaries demand compensation.  They march on Chicacao, burning down the municipal offices and taking hostage the provincial governor in San Francisco Zapotitlan.
A worker for the government's human rights prosecutor is assassinated.
Villagers pelt the president of congress (and former dictator) with rocks.
Armed men invade the house of a journalist, beating him, holding him hostage, and warning him not to publish further reports on corruption.
A mob beats a man to death after he tried to hold up a vendor in a market.

Violent protests erupt in support of former dictator Efrain Rios Montt, after the supreme court suspends his presidential campaign.  Protesters riot, surrounding the court, government offices, and the US embassy and a journalist is shot dead.
notes: (Black Thursday) in Guatemala.

issuenote: Gunmen attack a restaurant, killing two Guatemalans and an Italian exchange student.  A businessman suspected in smuggling is assassinated.
Hundreds of people opposed to the presidential candidacy of former dictator Efrain Rios Montt stage a march.
Armed men block a road and murder six members of a family.
Unknown parties raid the offices of the country's chief human rights prosecutor, leaving it robbed, searched and smeared with excrement.
The office of a human rights group is robbed and vandalized.
Protesters march against the World Trade Organization, which is meeting in Mexico.
Members of the Los Cholos gang beat an inmate to death, sparking a prison riot.
A mob beats journalists during a campaign rally for Efrain Rios Montt.
Street vendors protest against changes in bus routes which they say will hurt their businesses.  They blockade a road, but then gunmen on motorcycles attack them.
A mayor and candidate for the Senate is assassinated.
notes: Date is estimated.

issuenote: Ex-paramilitaries hold hostage four journalists to press the government for compensation for participating in the civil war.
Two women are trampled to death during an election day riot somewhere in the north.  Voters frustrated with long waits burn down polling stations in at least two cities.
Gunmen open fire on the vehicle of the country's chief anti-corruption prosecutor.
A mob of street vendors beats to death an accused robber.
A mob is angered with police arrest two men for public drunkenness.  The mob burns down the police station.
Unknown gunmen attack a car on the Pan-American Highway.
Men with automatic weapons hijack a bus full of Mormon tourists from the US.  The men rob the bus, killing one of the tourists.
Villagers lynch a teenager and attack two of his siblings.  The cause is unclear.
Rival street gangs battle, and a 1 year old girl is hit by stray bullets.
A violent highway robbery occurs -- a gunman shoots and wound an American missionary couple.
About 100 organizations mobilize tens of thousands to strike, block highways, schools and other services to protest plans for a tax hike.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: A mob contests the re-election of mayor Pablo Escobar and clashes with his supporters.
Gunmen attack and rob a group of American volunteers.
Paramilitaries protest outside of Congress to demand compensation for their services during the civil war.
Police try to clear a farm of 600 squatters, triggering a clash that leaves at least 12 dead.

elocal: Highway between Guatemala City and the Caribbean Coast.
ilocal: Highway between Guatemala City and the Caribbean Coast.
issuenote: Gunmen kill a journalist.
notes: Motive unknown.  Possibly crime.

issuenote: Protesters stone and burn public buses in reaction to a fare increase outside the capital.
Gunmen hold up a bus full of French and Belgian tourists.
Gunmen spray two homes with bullets, and then set them on fire.
A mob beats to death a man accused of assaulting an elderly man.  The mob douses the accused with gasoline and burns him to death.
Bus passengers try to fight off four gang members during an attempted robbery.  One passenger and one assailant is killed.
Bus passengers fight off a robbery attempt by a gang.  A passenger on board the bus opens fire, killing three gang members.

Protesters surround a police-escorted truck carrying equipment to a mine.  In order for the truck to pass through the town of Solola, a pedestrian bridge must be dismantled and then reassembled after the truck passes.
Air traffic controllers strike, shutting down air travel in Guatemala.  The government eventually fires the strikers.
Five people are abducted off the Guatemala City streets and executed in the countryside.  The victims are suspected gang members.
notes: Likely vigilante attack.

issuenote: 8000 teachers, unionists, farmers, leftist politicians, and academics wage massive street protests against the pending Central American Free Trade Agreement.
Hundreds of protesters try to break through police and storm the Legislative Palace in an effort to stop the passage of the CAFTA pact.
Protesters denouncing CAFTA clash with police in the capital, and stage scattered riots around the country.  Gunfire erupts on a highway in the northeast, leading to the death of one protester.
Catholics are unable to pray for Pope John Paul II because the church is closed due to a demonstration against CAFTA.
A judge is gunned down.
notes: There are two towns of this name in Guatemala.  This one is 260 km west of the capital.

issuenote: A federal prosecutor is gunned down.
Guatemalans protest against CAFTA.  Simultaneous protests occur in many of the Central American states.
A federal prosecutor is gunned down.
An angry mob kills six people accused of forming a band of robbers.
Three men are strangled and decapitated for allegedly robbing cars.
MS-13 and Mara-18 stage simultaneous riots in at least seven of the country's prisons, attacking each other with grenades, guns, and knives in a coordinated campaign of violence.
Rival prison gangs riot.
Armed men (labeled a death squad by the media) kill six in a single day in a poor neighborhood.
Gangs battle one another in a prison riot.
An angry mob burns to death a suspected thief and beats two others before turning them over to police.
The MS-13 gang riots, demanding televisions in their cells, conjugal visits, and the transfer of a group of prisoners not affiliated with the gang to another facility.

elocal: Pavoncito prison; Prison 50 km west of Guatemala City
ilocal: Prison 50 km west of Guatemala City
issuenote: Presumed gang members open fire on prison guards in two separate attacks.

elocal: Pavoncito prison; Prison 50 km west of Guatemala City
issuenote: Presumed gang members open fire on prison guards in two separate attacks.
About 20 bus drivers block several streets to demand that authorities capture and prosecute gang members who have been extorting and killing them.
A gang member is killed inside a prison after fighting breaks out between members of Mara-18.
Villagers use machetes to hack to death a man they believe to be a member of MS-13.
An angry mob beats two accused rapists, cutting a hand off of one and nearly doing the same to the other.
Gunmen attack a house associated with MS-13, killing 5 people inside.
Three bodies of Mara 18 members are discovered.
The bodies of Mara 18 members are discovered with signs of torture.  Vigilantes and rogue police are suspected.
The bodies of Mara 18 members are discovered with signs of torture.  Vigilantes and rogue police are suspected.
Armed men gun down three young women leaving a nightclub.  The high powered weaponry suggests that the killings are drug related.
An angry mob burns to death two people for allegedly stealing children.  The mob then tries to attack municipal buildings, including the police station and the town hall.
A mob burns to death three alleged robbers.
MS-13 members attack nonmembers in a bloody prison riot.
The governor of Solola province and one of his bodyguards are gunned down.
Armed ranch workers attack employees who were occupying the ranch land to demand payment for their work.
Gunmen assassinate three policemen in a largely uncontrolled area of the country.
Gunmen with assault rifles open fire on a pool hall.
Gunmen hold up a truck and make off with $8 million.
A mob attacks three men accused of attempted robbery, beating and kicking one to death and seriously injuring the others.
Teachers and labor groups rioted.
Rival prison inmates riot, battling one another before authorities storm the prison.

target1: Salvadoran members of the Central American Parliament
issuenote: Three Salvadoran members of the Central American Parliament are assassinated, including the son of an alleged mastermind of El Salvador's civil war death squads.  The arrested suspects are high ranking police investigators.
notes: Drug running, smuggling, and organized crime are suspected as possible motives, particularly given the events of February 25, 2007.

issuenote: Gunmen storm a prison and kill the four suspects arrested for the assassination of Salvadoran politicians on February 20, 2007, thereby eliminating key suspects and witnesses.
notes: The killings are believed to be a mafia hit aimed at stopping investigators from finding out who ordered the assassinations.

issuenote: Mayan indians protested against President Bush.
A gang riots in prison, taking several hostages.  Three people are killed before police storm the prison.
A leftist candidate for office is shot dead in front of his home.
notes: More than 50 political candidates and activists have been murdered this year alone.

issuenote: An activist with the Guatemalan Republican Front is gunned down in advance of elections.
notes: More than 50 political candidates and activists have been murdered this year alone.

issuenote: Riot police use tear gas to clear protesting families of the civil war dead who were demonstrating against a celebration of the armed forces.
A mayoral candidate for San Agustin Acasaguastlan is shot dead outside a pharmacy in Zacapa.
A candidate for the town council is shot dead.
Gangs with assault rifles battle against police.
Gangs battle with an undercover police agent.

A mob of villagers from the town of Chuapec, led by men with assault rifles, attack a police van and free an alleged drug trafficker being transported to trial.  It is unclear why the villagers assisted the gunmen.
Angry villagers riot, believing that a group of visiting teachers are apart of a kidnapping ring.  They hold the teachers hostage, and then capture the local mayor when he tries to mediate.
A campaign worker for a vice presidential candidate is shot to death on a busy street.
The teenage daughter of a congressional candidate is murdered.
Two candidates for office from the Enceuntro Por Guatemala Party are killed by assailants with automatic weapons.
A crowd accuses the mayor of a small town of bringing people from El Salvador to cast votes in his favor.  They riot, setting a voting booth on fire.  Police disperse them with tear gas.

target2: Secretary for the leading presidential candidate
issuenote: A presidential security guard and a candidate's secretary are shot and killed just weeks ahead of a runoff vote.
A shootout occurs among drug traffickers.
Robbers armed with machetes hack to death a US tourist on board a sailboat.
Villagers beat to death a man suspecting of helping to rob a bus and rape two passengers.
Unknown assailants murder a journalist by firing an arrow into his chest.
A gang attacks a bus full of Nicaraguan vendors.  They shoot the passengers, and then set the bus on fire.
notes: Somewhere in Zacapa province.

issuenote: A prison fight leaves 7 dead, including 5 killed by decapitation.

issuenote: Mexican and Guatemalan drug traffickers arguing about a horse race begin a series of gun battles that leave 17 dead.  AFP reports that that the clash occurred when the Guatemalans refused to join the Mexican cartel.
Gunmen open fire on a crowded holiday market.  The gunmen claim they caught the victims stealing.
Assailants kill two bus drivers.
notes: There have been 30 bus drivers killed up to this point in 2009.  Many of the attacks are blamed on the Gulf Cartel in Mexico.

issuenote: Army forces raid a recently discovered camp of the Gulf Cartel.  It is believed that members of the camp have been staging nearly daily attacks on bus drivers in Guatemala City.
Two attackers riding a motorcycle kill a journalist and seriously wound his cameraman.
notes: Soon thereafter, Guatemala passes a law banning more than one person from riding motorcycles.

issuenote: A local lawyer is killed.  The country's president is accused of the crime, triggering a massive political crisis.  Police officers and an ex-soldier are eventually arrested.
notes: In a plot worthy of a movie script, a UN commission determined that the lawyer asked relatives of his ex-wife to hire assassins to kill a supposed blackmailer. But the target he gave the killers was himself.

issuenote: Crowds march to demand the president's resignation after a video surfaces in which a lawyer accused the president of ordering his death just days before he was actually murdered.  Counter-protesters gather and jeer at the crowds.
notes: The UN then opens an investigation into the charges.

issuenote: 50,000 people demand a better justice system, and call for the impeaching of the president.
40,000 protesters show their support for the government during a political crisis in which the president is accused of murder.

Gang members try to extort protection money from bus drivers.  In southern Guatemala, they attack a bus, resulting in two deaths.  In the capital, they throw a grenade onto a bus, wounding 11 security guards.
notes: 139 bus drivers have died since the beginning of 2009.

issuenote: Four prison officials are shot to death in three separate attacks that authorities believe are retaliation for a jail crackdown.
Police are gunned down in retaliation by criminals.
Gang related gunmen attack police, killing one.
Maya Indians block entry points to the capital to protest the government's mining policies.  One person dies during the protests.
An assistant to the judge handling the case of the lawyer who blamed his death of Guatemala's president is himself assassinated by gunmen.
Gang members kill a German-Danish tourist.
A mob burns to death two men and a woman suspected of killing a local bus driver.
A crowd burns to death three people suspected of kidnapping and killing a young woman.
Villagers burn a man alive after accusing him of robbing and killing an elderly man.
A mob lynches and burns alive a man suspected of killing an elderly neighbor with a machete.
A mob fatally beats to death a man thought to be a criminal.  The crowd threatens to burn three women as well, but they are rescued by police.
Bus drivers clash with police to demand better security.
Unknown assailants toss a grenade onto a bus.
Unknown assailants torture a journalist to death.
A bomb is detonated by cell phone, killing 6 civilians.
Gunmen murder a family of six.
Six people are shot dead in a wave of violence.
Gunmen board a bus and spray the passengers with bullets.

30 to 40 assailants belonging to the Zetas, a Mexican drug cartel, massacre migrant workers on a remote farm while seeking out the owner for an assassination.  It is Guatemala's largest ever massacre linked to the drug gangs.
An angry mob lynches and burns suspected thieves.
Truckloads of gunmen surround a widely admired folk singer (Facundo Cabral) on his way to the airport in an apparent assassination attempt aimed at the singer's promoter.  The singer is gunned down.
An opposition lawmaker and his brother are gunned down.
About 12,000 people climb to the top of a volcano and link hands on a giant heart banner in order to draw attention to domestic violence.
notes: Volcan del Agua is an inactive volcano near the city of Antigua.

issuenote: Gunmen kill 8 people in a nightclub.
Thousands of indigenous farmers stage an eight day march to the capital from northern Guatemala to protest government back land seizures.

A mob seizes control of an army outpost in protestover the construction of a hydroelectric plant.  The mob also demands justice for a man killed hours earlier for what they claim was an attempt to intimidate them.
Education students confront the Interior Minister to demand a reopening of a dialogue on reforms to the national curriculum.  Police crack down with tear gas.
Protester gather to demonstrate against high electricity prices and education reform.  Police open fire on the protest.
Thousands of indigenous protesters protest against the killing of protesters by security forces in an earlier protest.
Unknown gunmen shoot dead the mayor of a small town.
Unknown gunmen burst into a clinic and shoot 7 people to death.
Unknown gunmen kill a federal prosecutor and six others.
Opponents of a mining project demonstrate.  Two mine security guards and a protester die during the riot.
Unknown gunmen shoot dead the mayor of a city.
Two armed groups suspected to be drug gangs clash.  Rumors spread that Jaoquin Guzman, head of the Mexican Sinaloa cartel, is killed during the firefight, but no evidence is found.
A man accused of shooting at a city bus is caught by an angry crowd and burned to death.
A journalist is assassinated by unknown gunmen.

Opponents of a Canadian-owned gold and silver mine project seize 23 police officers and hold them hostage.  Security forces move in, resulting in a clash in which one officer is shot dead.  Riots spread into nearby towns.

Opponents of a Canadian-owned gold and silver mine project seize 23 police officers and hold them hostage.  Security forces move in, resulting in a clash in which one officer is shot dead.  Riots spread into nearby towns.
Several dozen people protest outside a prison against the genocide conviction of former dictator Efrain Rios Montt.
Gunmen attack a police station, shooting dead eight officers and kidnapping the chief of police.
Gunmen assassinate a journalist.
Gunmen kill 11 people in a liquor store.
Three snipers belonging to a leftist group open fire on a bus carrying 28 US airmen.
Banana workers strike for higher wages.  Refinery workers stage a solidarity strike.  The strike ends when the army removes the strikers.
A faction of the communist Cinchoneros attempt an assassination against one of their group leaders that made peace with the military and announced incorporation into the political system.

target1: United Nations Central American Observer Group

Fired miners blockade a road into the American Pacific mining company.  Army troops try to remove the protesters, resulting in clashes and one civilian death.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Unknown attackers throw a grenade into a restaurant, killing workers of the state electrical company.  There is speculation that this is connected to labor unrest at the company, but this is not proven.
Soccer fans riot after Mexico beats Honduras 4-1 in a World Cup qualifier.
A grenade explodes harmlessly at a shopping center on election day.
Banana workers strike for better wages.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: 200 hundred supporters of the capital's mayor blockade streets after he is arraigned on corruption charges.
Inmates at a prison riot.  Some take hostages.  Others manage to escape.

The congress building is bombed by unknown parties.  The damage is minor.
notes: Speculation has it that the bombers are retired military personnel who are running security companies and are profiting from the climate of insecurity the bombings generate.

issuenote: Justa C attacked a court building where judges known for fighting organized crime, government corruption and military impunity work, one person killed.
A homemade bomb hurled from a speeding car Saturday damaged the Economy Ministry building and shattered windows over a wide area.
notes: This is the 40th bombing attack in the last 22 months.

notes: Found in Guatemala search

Inmates riot and escape from prison.
Public health workers strike and riot for higher wages.  Event ends when the army removes the striking workers from the hospitals.

Prisoners riot and escape.

Prison inmates riot.  Police foil an escape attempt.

actor1: Committee of People's and Indian Organizations
issuenote: 2000 protesters watch as a Indian rights group finishes a three month symbolic trial of Christopher Columbus.  The group finds him guild and 'executes' him by pelting a painting of him with arrows.
Prison guards open fire on a prison riot.

Pirates attack and rob a sailboat.  The tourists are rescued by ham radio operators.

A congressional candidate is assassinated in advance of elections.
Gunmen open fire on Liberal party headquarters in advance of an election.

Police clash with teachers and workers who are demanding pay increases.
Three assailants lob a bomb at the house of a man who ran for president in the 1980s.
Drug smugglers and police engage in a gun battle.

Rival prison gangs battle with grenades, guns, and knives smuggled into the El Porvenir prison.  Mara 18 tries to take over the prison in response to a weapon's raid by authorities, prompting violence from the other inmates.
Belgium's honorary consul to Honduras is shot dead.
A criminal gang massacres a family for unknown reasons.
Riots and clashes with police erupt over an upcoming deal with the IMF.
A gang attacks a bus in retaliation for a government security crackdown.
Left leaning parties lead protests against IMF austerity measures.
About 50 protesters gather during a visit by US Secretary of State Powell to decry the Central American Free Trade Agreement.
Gunmen murder a friar and steal Christmas bonuses from a home for the elderly.
Crowds at a Christmas toy giveaway in the National Stadium surge out of control, leading to a riot.
A man is murdered.  A note on his body threatens the president if he continues a crackdown on the country's gangs.
Hundreds gather on the one year anniversary of the invasion of Iraq to protest the war and Honduras' participation in it.
More than 100 employees and executives of Honduras' El Heraldo newspaper demonstrated outside a courtroom to protest the trial on defamation charges of one of their colleagues.

Members of a street gang gun down a policeman and abduct a legal advisor to the Security Ministry.  Police rescue him 8 hours later.
Five members of a family are violently executed by parties unknown.

A woman stands naked outside the Supreme Court to protest government corruption.
May Day protest against CAFTA.
Criminal gangs attack and rob a bus, killing a Canadian tourist.
Indigenous protesters take over a tourist site to pressure the government to honor a 1997 deal to disperse land to the Indians.
The leader of the National Party leads a protest, refusing to recognize the election victory of the Liberal Party.
Drug trading in the National Penitentiary leads to a battle among prison gangs using smuggled guns.
Unknown assailants attack an ambulance with grenades and automatic weapons.
Protesters decry the official beginning of the CAFTA pact.
A prison riot occurs when Mara 18 members ambush a rival gang in a ploy to gain more territory in the prison.

An anti-poverty protest sets up a roadblock.  A hotel owner loses his patience with the blockade and opens fire on the protest, killing a teacher.

An armed mob attacks a home as part of a long running land dispute.

The president orders a referendum allowing him to seek another term.  Congress, the military, and the Supreme Court call this move illegal and threaten to remove him from office.  Thousands demonstrate, demanding the president leave.
The military ousts president Manual Zelaya.
Pro-Zelaya protesters violently denounce the military coup; anti-Zelaya protesters demonstrate.
Pro-Zelaya protesters flock to a border crossing to support Manuel Zelaya's bid to reclaim the presidency.  There, they clash with police.
Public health workers strike to demand the return of president Zelaya.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Baton-wielding police fire tear gas to chase thousands of demonstrators away from the Brazilian embassy, where the deposed president is holed up.  The demonstrations continue for days, and two are killed by police.
A small protest in favor of Manual Zelaya occurs.
Over 100 protesters gather in the hotel where crisis negations are underway between supporters of Zelaya and supporters of the coup.
A grenade attack is reported at a radio station owned by Honduras' de facto leader.

Men armed with assault rifles burst into a shoe factory and open fire.  The massacre is blamed on gang rivalry over territory and drug trading.

A rebel group opens fire on a USAF base during a visit to Panama by President Bush.  There are no casualties.

Hundreds of protesters riot prior to and during a visit by US President Bush.  A speech by Bush is disrupted by protesters opposed to the invasion and tear gas wielding police, forcing Presidents Bush and Endara to flee to safety.
Gunmen attack US Army soldiers in a humvee during a visit by President Bush.  The incident occurs on a highway connecting Panama City to Colon.
Unknown assailants throw a bomb at a fuel storage facility operated by the US military.  A bomb squad disables the device.
Port workers and businessmen strike in favor of expanding the freeport in Colon to include native Panamanians.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Unknown bombers explode timed explosives at the Electoral Tribunal, the Foreign Ministry, and the office of the Tocumen International Airport.
notes: No claims of responsibility, although M-20 is speculated to be the culprit.

issuenote: Public transport workers strike to call on the government not to eliminate a gasoline subsidy.
Some 8000 doctors and officials of the Social Security system and 250 postal workers strike for higher wages and cost of living increases owed to them since 1988.
notes: End date is estimated.

actor1: State water and sewer system workers
issuenote: Public employees strike for high wages.

actor1: Movement of the Unemployed in Colon
issuenote: Protests occur, led by the Movement for the Unemployed, with demonstrators calling for jobs.
notes: Date is estimated.

issuenote: Bombs knock out four electrical pylons, causing blackouts around the country and electrical rationing in 8 out of 9 provinces.
geo_comments: Location is estimated given the description

issuenote: Police fire tear gas and birdshot on protestors demonstrating against unemployment.  The unrest is sparked by the deportation of Luis Ladeu, a leader of the unemployed movement in Colon.
Unknown kidnappers (speculated to be leftist Colombian guerrillas) kidnap three missionaries of the New Tribes Mission.
notes: Date is estimated.
geo_comments: Estimated middle point on Panama Colombian border

issuenote: 13000 taxi and bus drivers strike over plans to break up a 25 year old monopoly in the public transport sector.
Riots erupt after a jury clears seven military men of the 1985 killing of a leading opponent of Manuel Noriega.
Riots erupt after a jury clears seven military men of the 1985 killing of a leading opponent of Manuel Noriega.
Riots erupt after a jury clears seven military men of the 1985 killing of a leading opponent of Manuel Noriega.
6000 banana workers strike over government plans to sell land owned by Chiriqui Land Company to US-based Chiquita Banana.

actor1: Association of the Relatives of the Fallen
issuenote: 7000 protesters march to protest the US invasion that toppled Manuel Noriega and brought President Endara to power.
A homemade bomb causes a mid-air explosion on a commuter plane, which then crashes into the mountains, killing 21 people.  The dead include 12 Jewish businessmen and the mayor of Colon.
notes: Security officials and Jewish leaders fear these incidents are also linked to an incident in Britain.  Two Iranian nationals and a Lebanese are eventually detained by Panamanian authorities.  One of the dead is a Jewish businessman investigat

issuenote: Hundreds of Cuban refugees held at a US military base in Panama demonstrate against a deal struck between the US and Cuba concerning the crisis of 'boat people' fleeing Cuba.

ilocal: US base southeast of Panama City
issuenote: 8 Cuban refugees go on a hunger strike at a US naval base to protest their continued detainment, and to express their desires to travel to the US.
notes: Dates are estimated.

issuenote: About 1000 Cuban refugees riot at the Empire Range Complex of refugee camps.  The refugees are angry with the slow pace of resettlement.  236 US soldiers are wounded in the rioting.  The US soldiers specifically avoid taking hostile action.
notes: The Empire Range Comlex of refugee camps is somewhere in the Canal Zone.  (about 12 miles from Panama City)
geo_comments: Estimated near the city of Cocoli, Nicaragua

actor1: Coalition of 49 construction and banana workers' unions
issuenote: 7000 unionists stage a general strike over legislative proposals to curb the power of the unions.  Violent demonstrations erupt in the capital.

actor1: Coalition of 49 construction and banana workers' unions
issuenote: 7000 unionists stage a general strike over legislative proposals to curb the power of the unions.  Violent demonstrations erupt in the capital.
The Canal Free Zone's business association stages a one-day strike to protest a tax hike; about 2000 businessmen participate.  200 unemployed people gather to support the strike.
For the second time in a week, Canal Free Zone businesses close their doors and strike to protest a tax hike.
Rival prison gangs battle.
notes: The prison is 70 km east of the capital.

issuenote: Prisoners riot in La Modelo jail after two of them are accused of abusing other inmates and stealing their food.
Employees of a banana company strike over a dispute over raises for workers in packing sheds.
Students and workers protest outside a US base that is being considered for conversion into a US-operated anti-drug trafficking center.
30 protesters demonstrate and riot outside the US embassy.  They clash with police.
Hundreds gather to celebrate as two defendants are found innocent of killing a US soldier in 1992.
Three Greenpeace activists board a ship carrying nuclear waste bound for reprocessing in Japan.  Police make arrests.
4500 employees strike at the Chiriqui Land Company for higher wages.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Several hundred protesters form a human chain to protest a proposal to allow President Balladares to run for re-election.
20 imprisoned foreigners, including Colombians, one Israeli and one Coasta Rican, begin a hunger strike to demand televisions and radios in their cells.
notes: La Joyita prison is 40 km east of the capital.  End date is estimated.

issuenote: About 6000 people attempt to storm the Congress building in a protest against privatization.

Students demonstrate on a university campus against privatization and the government cancelation of several holidays (including Mother's Day).  Police enter campus, swinging batons and firing tear gas.
Colombian leftist rebels hijack a tourist helicopter.
geo_comments: Location is estimated given the description

issuenote: Protesters rally in front of the US embassy on the 10th anniversary of the American invasion.
Protesters rally outside the headquarters of Noriega's political party on the anniversary of the American invasion, where they burn him in effigy.
Rival gangs clash in a prison.
notes: La Joyita prison is 40 km east of the capital.
geo_comments: Estimated based on La Joya Airport (the nearest point)

issuenote: Armed men believed to be Colombian guerrillas or paramilitaries attack police.
geo_comments: Location not found, country centroid used

issuenote: Five police officers are injured when a demonstration by 500 students and 150 worker against public transport fare hikes escalates to a riot.
A late night protest against hikes in public transport fees escalates into a riot after police fire tear gas into a crowd of over 10,000 demonstrators.
3400 banana workers strike for higher wages.
Bus owners strike to protest a court decision blocking public transport fare increases needed to make improvements to vehicles.
Prison inmates riot.
Construction workers strike for better wages.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: 290 workers strike to demand increased compensation when their plant closes at the end of the year.
Doctors at public hospitals strike for overtime pay and shift premiums.
Drug traffickers murder a customs official in retaliation for his role in a heroine seizure.
Colombian paramilitaries attack a remote jungle village; two American journalists and one Canadian journalist are reported missing.

actor1: Front for the Defense of Social Security
issuenote: Strikes and demonstrations occur in protest of a government plant to privatize social security.  Demonstrations turn into violent riots in Panama City.
Thousands demonstrate against negotiations for a free trade agreement between the US and Panama.
Hundreds of Colombian prisoners stage a hunger strike to demand to be transferred to Colombia to serve out their sentences.
notes: End date is estimated.
geo_comments: Estimated based on La Joya Airport (the nearest point)

issuenote: Thousands protest any reform in social security law that might lower benefits or raise the minimum retirement age.
High school students and construction workers riot to protest proposals for pension reform.  The riots escalate into general strikes by more than 50 labor unions.  Police make hundreds of arrests.
Hundreds are arrested during nationwide riots over proposed pension reforms.
A couple hundred students and professors hold vigils and rallies to oppose a visit by US president Bush.
60 journalists march to protest a proposed gag law.
200 people protest outside the Israeli embassy over Israel's attacks on the Gaza Strip.
Violent strikes by banana workers against a proposed new law weakening the power of unions.
Protesters demonstrate against a new law that makes it easier for foreigners to invest in the mining industry.
Several dozen indigenous Panamanians armed with spears clash with riot police over recent changes to the country's mining law.
Several hundred indigenous Panamanians armed with spears clash with riot police and blockade the Pan-American Highway over recent changes to the country's mining law.
About 6000 Panama Canal workers strike to demand higher wages.

Indigenous Panamanians protest a proposed mining law by blocking the Pan-American Highway, demanding that a mining ban remain in place in their homeland.  Police break up the protests with lethal force.
Protesters angry with legislation to sell land from a duty-free zone set tires on fire and toss stones at police, who respond with warning shots.
Protesters angry with legislation to sell land from a duty-free zone riot in Colon and Panama City.  Police use deadly force.
Hundreds of people lock access to the duty free port to demand greater public investment in the region.
Farmers and indigenous people protest against a planned hydroelectric dam, which they claim will displace thousands of people.  Police crack down on the demonstrators, who fight back with rocks.
